@node editorsdesk "From The Editor's Desk"
@toc contents
============================================================================
	            @{b}From The Editor's Desk@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

  Welcome to issue 6 of WhatIff? and what an issue we have for you this 
  time round.  To start off with we welcome @{"Ivan Sorensen" link ivansorensen} to the WhatIFF?
  writing staff.  For his first issue  he has written two articles:  
  @{"Floppy Disks and You" link floppygotek} and @{"Authenticity, the Amiga and You" link realamiga} bringing his
  expertise and knowledge to the the magazine.  Also just for this issue we 
  also have two submissions from @{"Carl Svensson's" link carlsvensson}: @{"ARexx Stems as Mock Data" link arexxstems}
  and @{"Little Things That Made The Amiga Great" link littlethings}.  Even though his submissions 
  are just for this issue we look forward to him writing for the magazine 
  again the near future.  

  As if that is not enough we have reviews of the A500 Mini, Infinity Music 
  Player v3, AmiSSL Classic 5.2 and The LightWave Book.  The Brilliance and
  LightWave 101 tutorials continue with the latter look at the LW-Config
  file and how it can help in streamlining your work process.

  @{"John Scolieri" link johnscolieri} is back with an article for Amiga OS4.1 users with a
  tutorial on reading and creating ADFs and @{"Kevin Saunders" link kevinsaunders} 
  updates us on his latest 
  game projects regarding the Vampire series of computers. As you can see
  this issue is quite packed and this is all thanks the writers for their
  amazing contributions to the magazine.
 
  Some of the more eagle eyed of you might have noticed a new section on 
  the main page: @{"Amiga Vendors" link amigavendors} this list will be updated each time a 
  anew Amiga dealer is found.  If you are selling Amiga goods and are not on
  the list then contact us so we can add your details.

  I hope you will enjoy this issue and what it has to offer, it is incredible
  to think we have made it to issue 6 already.  While there are other more
  professional printed Amiga magazines available I hope that we can offer
  something a bit different to them.  If you have any suggestions or want
  to contribute to the magazine in anyway please contact us at:

  submissions@whatiff.info  
      
@endnode

@node shelltalk "Free For All About The Amiga"
@toc contents
============================================================================
	               @{b}Shell Talk@{ub} - by: @{"Daniel Reimann" link danielreimann} 
============================================================================

  @{b}How I Rediscovered My Floppy Disks@{ub}

  What are, among many other nice things, the advantages of having a baby? 
  You get to know your surroundings from a completely new perspective! On 
  our living room bookshelf, which is IKEA of course ;), there are two 
  separate compartments on the bottom: one is filled with magazines, hiking 
  maps and travel books, the other with my two Amiga floppy disk boxes and 
  quite a few other boxes.
 
  Currently, my child has developed two habits, which results in both 
  shelves being completely cleared out :) He has a preference for hiking 
  maps, which are unfolded with great pleasure and don't consist of only 
  one piece. In addition, he also enjoys floppy disk boxes. There are two 
  of them: the Verbatim "Deluxe" version, which offers a small plastic 
  cover for each disk (like Boeder) and the Profex. Here is my complete 
  collection: 

  Now I don't know if it's sacrilege to keep floppy disks not in 
  professional plastic boxes/slipcases, but just in the original cardboard 
  boxes.  However, it was the trigger for me to dig back into old memories. 

  Vividly I can remember the various rummaging through boxes and walls in 
  the local electronics store, in which the disks of various suppliers were 
  presented. And every time the question came up: do I take the cheap 
  no-name parts or do I treat myself to a box of the brand suppliers? 
  As it turned out, I gladly reached for Boeder & Co and treated myself to 
  a variety of colourful disks. Even in the 90s, one was already aware of 
  sustainability, see KAO. And the no-name boxes were semi-professionally 
  glued together and thus used as a kind of big box. 

  Now some of you may not believe it, but a considerable part of my floppy 
  disk (collection) contains software from Aminet.  Of course, like many 
  others, I used a modem on my Amiga 1200!  First, a 28.8k modem, which 
  drove me crazy, because I never managed to get a noise-free dial-up, and 
  later finally a 56k modem. At that time, in the mid-90s, I was studying 
  and Aminet was the best place where I could get software quickly and for 
  free - yes, at that time dial-up at home still cost something though ;)

  Where is all the download software from Aminet?  In the computer cabinet
  of course!.  It felt like there was a new version of Voyager and Co every 
  week and I could hardly keep up... 

  Are floppy disks now just an outdated greeting from times long past? I 
  have to admit, it's been a while since I put the last floppy disk into the 
  A1200 (but that also has to do with the current "computer offspring"). On 
  the one hand, of course, they consume a lot of space. For the little bit 
  that's on there...On the other hand, it's very pleasant to have an 
  antithesis to this "WLAN/streaming/'file-shuffling' world. And even if it 
  might seem contradictory regarding the 'wild copy times' on the Amiga: 
  doesn't such a disk better symbolise the efforts and value behind the 
  development of the software? In any case, my curiosity is aroused and I 
  will be rummaging around in the boxes some more ...


@endnode

