@node lightwave3dbookreview "The LightWave 3D Book Review"
@toc reviews
============================================================================
	    @{b}The Lightwave 3D Book Review@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

  @{b}Product Name@{ub}                    
  The LightWave 3D Book - Tips, Techniques, and Ready-to-Use Objects
  2nd Edition

  @{b}Available From@{ub}
  Amazon/eBay/Used Book Stores

  @{b}Price@{ub}
  $1-20

  @{b}The Lightwave 3D Book Review@{ub}
  LightWave 3D is an very user friendly programme, especially when put
  against the likes of Imagine.  However to truly get at the true
  power that LightWave affords a little guidance is needed.  There are
  a large selection of books for the modern versions of LightWave 
  centred on Windows and Mac OS computers, however there have not been
  any new books written about LightWave 3D and the Amiga.
  
  The majority of the books that have recently been written about Amiga
  concentrate on games and the history of Commodore.  Where it comes to
  guides or tutorials the options are a bit more limited.  In the mid 90s
  after Lightwave 3D was released as a standalone programme there were a 
  number of tutorial books written.  I was lucky enough to find one that
  advertised in Amiga World and had it shipped over the States.

  This book had some great tutorials and hints for beginners and veteran
  users alike.  Since starting the LightWave 101 series I have been
  wanting to dive back into the book again to help me with the series
  but unfortunately the original book has been lost to time.  Having
  had an unsuccessful search for it on the internet I decided to find
  an alternative book.
 
  After much searching I realised that there are not many books that 
  deal with the Amiga and Lightwave 3.5.  However, after much  an
  exhausting search I came across a book titled 'The Lightwave 3D Book' 
  released in 1997.  

  This book peaked my interest due to two factors, it was created by the 
  editors of LightWavePro Magazine which I had read a few times in the
  past, and they had often mentioned the Amiga and the book mentions
  LightWave 3.5 which as far as I know was only on the Amiga.  

  With my hopes high I ordered the book from Amazon for the princely sum 
  of $10.00 plus  shipping.  It should be noted that this book can also 
  be picked up for quite a bit cheaper as noted in the cover the of the 
  book when it was sold for (Ahem) $1.00. 

  @{b}The Book@{ub}
  The book itself is roughly A4 size but a slightly wider, it comes in at
  287 pages and includes a CD-Rom with textures, objects, plugins and
  applications (including ones for the Amiga!).  It is a hefty book with
  thick pages and is printed in black & white.  

  Since this is a collection of guides from a magazine the contents are 
  organised by subject instead of publishing date, as was done in the 
  first edition.  This makes it easier to jump in and out of the book and 
  find something you need based on a particular topic.  

  The tutorials themselves are quite detailed and relatively easy to 
  follow, in some instances there are grey scale photos but in general 
  they are not needed due to the precise writing.

  If you are a beginner to LightWave 3D this book however will not be for 
  you.  The articles presume a certain affinity and experience with 
  LightWave 3D which is understandable since they come from a magazine
  that was solely dedicated to LightWave.

  This brings me onto the writing style, while the topics covered are
  serious in nature, the writing tone is light with humour often sprinkled
  into the articles.  This helps make something that could be quite dry 
  reading into an enjoyable experience in itself.

  The authors themselves are quite the heavyweights in the 3D animation 
  world having worked on Babylon 5, seaQuest and RoboCop The Series to 
  name just a few shows.

  It makes for a fascinating read almost 30 years later as the animators
  detail the hurdles and tricks they used on some of the biggest shows
  in the 90s.  Reading about them using our lovely Amiga in the process
  just makes it so much more enjoyable!

  Even if you are not interested in learning about animating in LightWave
  or are a beginner the articles about the creation process are a great 
  read in themselves.  It is something that I would like to see more of 
  featured in the Amiga history books.  The Amiga realy was revolutionary
  with the Video Toaster and LightWave and deserves more recognition for
  what it contributed to TV and movies in the 90s.

  For those of you who are interested in learning more about LightWave
  techniques then this book has a very good learning curve and each
  tutorial is explained in simple enough English as to not make it too
  hard to follow.  With YouTube having become such a large part of life
  it is easy to forget how useful a guide book like The LightWave 3D
  book can be.  You can move at your own pace and not have to worry about
  pausing or rewinding the video or even worse, the dreaded pop up 
  adverts right when you are getting to the hard part of the video.

  @{b}The CD@{ub}
  Yes,this book comes with CD and even has some Amiga programmes which
  still manages to surprise me.  

  The drawers on the CD are as follows:

  DEMOS	   :	Some videos/animations done the leading animators of
		the time.	

  DOCS     :    Contains all the Readme files for certain Scenes,
		Objects. 

  LW3_5    :    Specifically for LightWave 3.5 and earlier, it contains
		all the Scenes/Objects/Images configured for the older
		versions of LightWave.

  OTHER    :    Demo of LIGHT-ROM textures, images and objects.

  PLUGINS  :	PowerView Plugins for PC and Amiga!

  PROGRAMS :    Useful programmes for the Amiga and PC.

  SETUPS   :    Setup files for one of the tutorials lised in the book.

  As you can see there is quite a bit of content for the Amiga on the 
  CD-Rom which was a pleasant surprise.  While the Amiga was very much 
  alive for me in 1997 the rest of world had forgot about the Amiga and
  so it is nice to see the Amiga represented so well in the book.

  @{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}
  If you are looking for a book to help you understand the basics of how
  to use LightWave, this is not for you.  However if you already have a
  basic understanding of LightWave and have created some simple objects
  or animations then this book will probably suit you to a T.  The topics
  covered are wide ranging and detailed enough so that you will not have
  too many questions.  The book contains lot of Amiga centric articles 
  as well which is always a plus.  The book can be found quite easily on 
  Amazon or other online bookstores, it can range from very cheap to 
  reasonable.

  There are not many Amiga tutorial books available anymore and if you
  want to learn more about LightWave then this is a book that I highly
  recommend.

  @{b}Pros and Cons@{ub}
  + Many topics
  + Easy to read writing style
  + Covers the Amiga
  + CD Rom included
  - Not for first time users
@endnode

@node impreview "Infinity Module Player Review"
@toc reviews
============================================================================
	   @{b}Infinity Module Player Review@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

  @{b}Product Name@{ub}
  Infinity Module Player (IMP) v3.355

  @{b}Created By@{ub}
  Pawel Nowak

  @{b}Available From@{ub}
  Aminet

  @{b}Price@{ub}
  Free/Donation

  @{b}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}
  68K OS 2.04+/PPC/MorphOS/i386-AROS
  Network connected Amiga 

  @{b}Machine Used For Testing@{ub}
  Commodore Amiga 1200
  Classic WB + 3.2 Kickstart
  TF 1260 

  @{b}Infinity Module Player (IMP) Review@{ub}
  Listen (to) songs from (the) internet - over 168,000 files! (mods, 
  SIDs, AHXs, XMs...), that is the first in the readme file that is 
  on Aminet.  The brain child of Polish programmer Pawel Nowak, IMP
  can be viewed as an Amiga version of streaming audio software like
  Spotify or Apple Music, but instead of an audio stream the music is
  downloaded straight to your Amiga and played, then when the song has
  finished another one will be downloaded and played and so on.  Not
  streaming as we know it persay but I think something that is uniquely
  Amiga and brimming with potential.  

  Currently there are a number of internet radio stations playing Amiga
  music but it has been limited to the more powerful Amigas or PCs/Mac
  due to the need to decode the audio stream fast enough to be listenable.              

  Luckily a few pioneering individuals realised that it would be possible
  to stream mods directly to the Amiga meaning that the lower spec Amigas
  that were connected to the internet could enjoy 24/7 streaming of the 
  latest and classic mods.  Of the few programmes that have been released 
  Infinity Module Player caught my eye or shall I say ear that is.

  If you are a regular of EAB then you will probably already know about
  the IMP thread, which has the latest updates and fixes posted there
  first.  If not, I recommend heading over to EAB and checking out the 
  thread as it is interesting to see how the programme has evolved from
  something that was originally used mainly by Polish Amiga users to
  something that is being used by Amiga users all over the world.

  This will be a short review and introduction to the Infinity Module 
  Player (IMP).

  @{b}Installation@{ub}
  IMP has gone through several changes since it's inception, starting as
  a programme that ran in the shell it now has a proper interface made
  up up several windows; a command menu, player control, scope, and a
  chat window.

  What raises it above the other mod streamers is its ease of
  installation.  Just download the software from Aminet, copy it to your
  location of choice and double click on the icon.  By default there is
  tool icon so you will need to run it either from the Shell or click again
  on 'Ok' when the execute window pops up.  You will need to have a TCP
  client running in the background but other than that, there is nothing
  else required.  Upon first starting you are taken to a new custom screen
  which seems to be set at PAL Hires screen and asked to create a new
  user name, from then on the user name will be saved not requiring you
  to enter it again.

  While it goes into a custom screen by default you are able to change
  it to a public screen and view it on Workbench.  Other than these few
  steps that is all that is needed to run IMP.

  @{b}In Use@{ub}
  Once you have the programme up and running you have four windows to
  contend with.  The programme by default runs in a custom screen but
  this can be changed to run in any resolution or on the Workbench in a
  Public screen.  I chose to use it on the Workbench since I run my
  Amiga in HIGHGFX: Super HiRes, which gives me plenty of desktop real
  estate to have all of IMP's windows and still have space to open other
  windows and move files around.

  After you have created your user name the programme will not do
  anything until you click on the play button.  This was the only issue
  that I had with the programme and it is probably just me.  However I
  found it a little hard to locate the play button, I was looking for
  something more akin to the traditional Play/Pause button found on
  other music players.  In IMP's case it is just a thin arrow with
  another button with two arrows next to it.  Probably 99% of IMP users
  will not have any trouble with this but it was something that stuck
  out at me.

  Getting back to the layout, I mentioned above the command menu,
  playback, scope and chat windows.  One window in particular that I
  enjoyed was the 'SCOPE' window which shows the four channels and
  tracker patterns.  Having the ability to see how the song is
  structured and plays, creates more personal connection with the music.
  When listening to MP3s or streaming music on PC/Macs you can't see how
  the structure of the music however thanks to the MOD format we can see
  how the music was made and as one who also makes music on the Amiga I
  find this most enjoyable.  However for those who do not have the space
  for the window or are not interested it can be closed and re-opened
  again by clicking on 'SCOPE'.

  Let's take a deeper look at the Menu Window, it is possible to control
  IMP via the menu bar as such all control is done via buttons.  I will
  list each button and what it does:
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------

  CHAT   - Opens the chat window.
  DISK   - Gives you access to other files held on the IMP server.
  FAVS   - A list of the tracks that you favourited.
  TOPS   - The most played files, click module name to play.
  STASH  - A place to store your own MODS, only available to donators.
  DISCO  - a funky screen with moving colours, simple but fun effect.
  ZGR3D  - A small game that reminds me of Digger.
  SCOPE  - Displays the module patterns.
  HELP   - Did not seem to do anything.
  SEARCH - Find a particular module.
  SAVE   - Save the current MOD to your Amiga.
  TYPE   - Set which format of songs you want to listen to: Modules, Sids,
           AHX, XM, and DBM.
  MODE   - Choose if you want to play only the songs you liked, only with
     	   likes, ones you searched, never played or all songs.
  PREFS  - Palette, Screen, Fonts, Switxh Workbench, LED Filter: On/Off
  TEST   - Tests your network connection speed.

  ------------------------------------------------------------------------
  As you can see there is a lot functionality to IMP that goes beyond a
  simple MOD streamer.  It pays to deep dive into the menu and learn how
  it works and what is possible.

  @{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}
  The idea of a MOD streamer is very appealing, while I wish I had the
  time to search all the MODs myself the reality is that there is just
  too many and not enough time.  Infinity Module Player is the Spotify
  for Amiga MODs, it makes listening to a large library of music as
  simple as clicking a button.  The version that I reviewed v3.355 was
  quite stable and I only experienced one issue where the whole screen
  became garbled in red and yellow.  However after a quick reboot and
  everything was back to normal, the only effect I had was that I lost
  part of this review.

  This software has a mainstay on my Amiga, in fact somuch so that I 
  have ended up buying a mini hifi and have it hooked up to the Amiga 
  24/7, streaming music most of the day, much tothe annoyance of my wife.  

  The ease of use, the multiple functionality, the social aspect and the 
  massive library of MODs makes this one of the best pieces of software I 
  have reviewed of recent.  It is fantastic that the programme is available 
  for free, though I recommend  donating to the author for his hard work.  

  Bottom line, download this now, if you don't have a network connected 
  Amiga, get it connected, and hook your Amiga up to proper speakers and 
  boogy on down to the tunes.  Right time for me to bust some moves!

  @{b}Pros and Cons@{ub}
  + Easy to install
  + Loads of functionality
  + Stable
  + Free
@endnode

@node amissl5review "AmiSSL 5 Review"
@toc reviews
============================================================================
	    	  @{b}AmiSSL v5 Review@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

  @{b}Product Name@{ub}                    
  AmiSSL v5.2

  @{b}Created By@{ub}
  AmiSSL Open Source Team

  @{b}Available From@{ub}
  Aminet

  @{b}Price@{ub}
  Free

  @{b}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}
  68K Amiga OS 3.0+/68020+
  Network connected Amiga 

  @{b}Machine Used For Testing@{ub}
  Commodore Amiga 1200
  Classic WB + 3.2 Kickstart
  TF 1260 

  @{b}What Is AmiSSL@{ub}
  If you are new to AmiSSL, in a nutshell it is a collaborative effort to
  develop OpenSSL as a shared library for all Amiga systems (Amiga OS, 
  Morph OS, AROS, and so forth).  SSL stands for Secure Sockets Layer
  and is the standard technology used for keeping an internet connection
  secure and protecting any sensitive data being sent between two 
  systems.  As such it is now a requirement for any and all websites 
  so if you plan to surf the web on your classic Amiga then  AmiSSL 
  is a necessity.  Lucky for us the library is being distributed  for 
  free via Aminet or the AmiSSL website.

  @{b}In Use@{ub}
  Installation is taken care of with the standard Workbench installer
  and it is simple and quick.  One thing that is different from the last
  version of AmiSSL v4 is that users with the TF1260 060LC cards can now
  install the 060 version.  Previously this would cause Amigas with the 
  LC060 chip to freeze, the reason being the LC has no FPU and the v4 of 
  AmiSSL was most likely looking for a full 060 with FPU.  

  I am happy to report that when I installed v5 and chose 060 the 
  installtion went smoothly.  More so when I tested the latest version of 
  AmiSSL with AmiGemini which requires AmiSSL there was no crash and it 
  was visibly faster than previously.

  It is great to see AmiSSL supporting more hardware and in particular the
  Terrible Fire cards.  If you have an TF1260 with the LC 060 card and wantt
  to browse Gemini capsules or use the latest version of IBrowse then you 
  will need this.

  @{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}
  As a review this is very short and lacking on details however all you
  really need to know is that if you are planning to surf the Internet
  with the latest browsers or AmiGemini, then you need this.  You don't
  have to choose (68020/030/040/080 or MorphOS) anymore if you have
  a TF1260LC card as it seems the 060s without FPUs are also supported.
@endnode

@node a500minireview "A500 Mini Review"
@toc reviews
============================================================================
	    	 @{b}A500 Mini Review@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

  @{b}Product Name@{ub}                    
  The A500 Mini

  @{b}Created By@{ub}
  Retro Games - www.retrogames.biz

  @{b}Available From@{ub}
  Any electronics store

  @{b}Price@{ub}
  £119.99

  @{b}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}
  HDMI TV/Monitor

  @{b}The First New Amiga Since 1996!@{ub}
  Well calling the The A500 Mini as a true new Amiga might be stretching
  the truth a bit but since we have not had a real Amiga since 1996
  beggars can't be choosers as the old saying goes.  You may be wondering
  why we are reviewing the A500 Mini in WhatIFF? since the magazine does
  not cover games, a good question.  Well to be perfectly honest the
  opportunity to review new Amiga hardware in whatever form does not come
  up often, so it was decided to review the mini A500 in the WhatIFF?
  way.

  @{b}First Impressions@{ub}
  The box reminds you right away of the cartoon classics pack that was 
  released in the UK, the colour scheme and layout carry a heavy load
  of nostalgia.  Upon opening the box you are presented with the smallest
  Amiga to date, a lovingly recreated A500.  Under the mini computer you
  can find the mouse and control pad, as you have probably already seen in
  the photos of other reviews the mouse is a slightly smaller re-creation
  of the classic tank mouse that came with the A500s.  The pad is 
  reminiscient of the CD32 pad, this might divide opinion, personally I 
  liked the CD32 pad as it was big and chunky and fit my hands nicely. 
  The A500 Mini version however is a bit smaller and can feel a little
  cramped after long gaming sessions.

  Taking a closer look at the A500 itself, the attention to detail is a 
  delight to behold, all the original lines, font and keyboard details
  are there to take you back to your youth.  Looking at the side you have
  a limited recreation of the floppy disk and on the right the lines of
  the casing joints, unfortunately the side slot cover is missing.  A
  few others have mentioned this and I have to concur that it seems like
  a missed opportunity with the floppy disk area, it would have been nice
  to have an USB slot there when using WHDLoad games.

  On the back you have the HDMI, USB-C, and three USB ports, right away 
  you feel this is a little limited considering if you want to have an
  external keyboard, mouse, joypad and additional games.  The power
  switch is on the back and is a simple push button.  Upon plugging
  everything in and pushing it the red powerlight comes on bringing back
  again a surprising rush of memories, who ever thought seeing a 
  rectangle red LED could be so emotive.

  @{b}Starting Up@{ub}
  After pressing the power button you have a few seconds of a black 
  screen followed by a white screen with the A500 logo and a quick
  bounce of a half boing ball.  Simple but slick and effective.  The
  rest of your A500 mini experience takes place in the game carosele
  move to the left or right to highlight your game.  Press the A 
  button red start a game, you also have 4 game save slots that can 
  be accessed by pushing down, for those extra hard games.

  To access the Options press Menu on the control pad, from here you
  can change the display optons, mouse sensitivity, music volume,
  power LED settings, language, advanced options such as 50 or 60 hz
  and expert mode.  When you use WHDLoad games you will be able to
  change more settings such JIT, changing the way the Copper works
  and more.  The setting options are quite encompassing, going
  beyond the typical settings offered with other mini consoles and
  for this I commend the creators.

  For this review we will not cover the games because what may be junk
  for one is gold for another and we do not review games here.  However
  we will look at what you can do beyond the games and see if the A500
  could be a nice alternative to buying a 'real' Amiga.  As stated above
  it is possible to load WHDLoad games but what if you want to use the
  Amiga for more than games, is that possible with the A500 Mini?

  @{b}Beyond Games@{ub}
  First you will need to prepare a USB thumbdrive, update the A500 Mini
  to the latest firmware and prepare an HDF file.  At the moment the
  A500 Mini does not officially support HDF files but with the latest
  firmware update ADF support is now included.  To access your HDF file
  you will need to bring the Amiberry configure screen up and this can
  be done by editing one of the .uae files.  The easiest way to do this
  is to download any WHDLoad game and keep it in the .lha format.  Play
  the game once on the A500 Mini and then shutdown the mini.  Take the
  USB drive from your mini and look for the game you just played, for
  example if you downloaded and played Lemmings.lha, look for the file
  and below it you will see Lemmings_ol.uae, copy this file over to your
  computer and rename it to .txt.  Now you can edit it as a text file,
  next you will need to add four lines to the top of the text file:

			amiberry.open_gui=F12
                        amiberry.save_state_on_exit=true
			amiberry.ignore_gui=false
			use_gui=yes
  
  Save the file and put the extension back to .uae, most of your probably
  already know what these four lines will do, open the Amiberry configure
  screen.  Now when you run this game, instead of the game starting the
  Amiberry screen will pop up, from here you can change the settings like
  you would as if you were running in WinUAE or UAE for Mac.  Change the
  CPU, chipset, add floppy disks or ... and this is what we are looking
  for add a HDF file.  For my experiment I used ClassicWB LITE, and I am
  happy to say it worked.  From here I was able to run Workbench and use
  the A500 Mini for much more than games.  You will need to find a good
  keyboard and probably a USB hub but this proves that with a little work
  the A500 Mini could become a replacement Amiga.

  What I described above was just a simple example and if you are not
  comfortable changing settings or have not used UAE before then you
  might want to do this with someone else who has experience with Amiga
  emulation software.

  @{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}
  The A500 Mini is a well planned and excuted minature Amiga, it is
  easy to setup for beginners, comes with all the necessary utilities,
  connects to your modern TV and has the ability of add games with the
  minimum of effort and fuss.  As it stands it is a great option for 
  playing Amiga games on your TV or with family.  It is particularly
  relevant today with the prices of Amiga hardware skyrocketing and 
  existing hardware becoming more fragile and rare.  If you want to
  introduce your children to the joys of Amiga gaming without having to
  worry if you will need to take out a loan to pay for repairs if they
  become too excited then the A500 Mini is a great option.

  Beyond the game playing the fact that it can be hacked to use HDF files
  tips it from being a good buy to a fantastic purchase.  In essence you
  have a fully useable Amiga that has USB ports and can be plugged into a 
  modern display without any extra hardware.  Great for the beginner and
  veteran Amiga user alike.    

  @{b}Pros and Cons@{ub}
  + Easy to setup
  + Ability to add games and HDF
  + Relatively cheap compared to real hardware
  + Looks great!
  - Lack of USB ports
  - No working internal keyboard
@endnode

