@node adfsamigaos41 "ADFs With Amiga OS4.1"
@toc guides
=============================================================================
        @{b}How to read/ write ADF's with AmigaOS4.1@{ub}  - by: @{"John Scolieri" link johnscolieri}
=============================================================================

  @{b}How to read/ write ADF's with AmigaOS4.1@{ub}

  Amiga Disk Files,or more commonly known as ADF's, are used by Amiga
  users to backup their original floppies as well as disk virtualization 
  i.e. access an ADF files on Workbenches if it were a physical drive.

  When I first bought my AmigaOne X1000 motherboard over a decade ago
  my trusty Amiga 1200 at the time had some hardware issues I couldn't
  figure out and a ton of disks which sadly were never backed up...I mean 
  I knew I had my 1200 hard drive backed up but never thought about
  backing up my disks until my Amiga broke down. My X1000 
  didn't have a connector to directly use my external Amiga disk drive 
  so in order to use my Amiga disks I had to purchase a Catweasel floppy
  controller from Individual Computers (icomp.de) which allowed me to 
  use a commonly used PC floppy drive in my X1000 as if it were an 
  Amiga 3.5 drive. With the 3.5" drive installed the next step was to 
  install SuperDiskImage by Ian Gledhill over at his website
  (http://www.retroreview.com/iang/Catweasel/). Using SuperDiskImage
  is quite straight forward as follows:

  To create an ADF file from a real 3.5" floppy-

  1- Insert disk into 3.5" drive 
  2- Select which drive you want to use (Unit 0 or Unit1)
  3- Click the 'Read Disk' button at top of screen
  4- The blocks at mid screen will turn from black to green after being 
     successfully read.  Note: If a block cannot be successfully read it 
     will appear red.
  5- Once all blocks have been read remove the master disk from drive
     and save the new ADF file by typing the name of the disk into the
     'Image' requester (don't forget to add the '.adf' at the end of the 
     file name) and choose the drive/ partition/ folder to save to.

  To copy an ADF file to a real 3.5" floppy-

  1- Follow items 1 & 2 as above.
  2- Use the file requester to select the file from your hard 
     drive/removable media etc.
  3- Click the 'Write Disk' button at top of screen
  4- The image file selected will be copied track by track to the selected 
     disk.

  If you have some copy protected disks you want to backup you need to do
  the following:

  1- Open a text editor to edit DEVS:NSDPatch.cfg
  2- Add the following lines:

  DEVICE trackdisk.device UNIT 0 MAPTODEVICE catweasel.device MAPTOUNIT 0 MACHINE=machinetype
  DEVICE trackdisk.device UNIT 1 MAPTODEVICE catweasel.device MAPTOUNIT 1 MACHINE=machinetype

  3- Install NSDPatch from aminet (if you haven't done so already)
  4- Copy your SYS:Storage/DOSDrivers/TD0 to SYS:Storage/DOSDrivers/DF0 
  5- Reboot

  If you are into using emulators on your AmigaOS4 system the Catweasel 
  allows you to use your original Commodore 64/128, MS-DOS, ATARI, Texas 
  Instruments, Apple Macintosh, Acorn BBC, Sinclair Spectrum, Amstrad CPC, 
  Tatung Einstein and Triumph-Adler Alphatronic disks! Of course you still 
  need working drives from each system.

  Many thanks to Individual Computers for creating the catweasel cards and to 
  Ian Gledhill for creating SuperDiskImage.

  Cheers,
  G. Scolieri
@endnode

@node lightwave101 "LightWave 101 - Editing Configurations Files"
@toc guides
============================================================================
 	    @{b}LightWave 101 - Part 5@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================
  
  @{b}What Are LW-config & MOD-config?@{ub}
  Welcome to the fifth installment in the LightWave 101 series, for this
  issue we will be looking at the two config files: LW-config (LightWave)
  and MOD-config (Modeler), both files can be found in the Toaster/3D
  directory.  The tutorial will be split into two parts, this part we will
  concentrate on the LW-config file and next time on the MOD-config file.
 
  If you remember back to the first installment in this series we looked 
  at getting your assigns setup so LightWave would load correctly and 
  allow you to access to the surfaces, objects, scenes etc. without 
  causing issues.  

  This is tutorial will go beyond setting up your assigns.  When you load 
  LightWave and open a file requster you may have noticed that the choice 
  of drives at the top may not be the same naming convention as your 
  drives, for example LightWwave's the default device names are:

		Parent | DF0 | HD0 | HD1 | RAM 

  In my instance the drives are not named HD0 and HD1, they are DH0 and 
  DH1.  As such if I click on the HD0 an error requestor will pop up, 
  well this can be fixed by editing the LW-config and MOD-config files.

  @{b}LightWave Config file@{ub}
  Let's have a look at the LW-Config file first, below is a listing of my
  config file and I will show you what I need to fix.

  LWCO
  0
  -The two lines above are file identifiers and should not be changed.

  FileReqPreset1 DF0 DF0:
  FileReqPreset2 HD0 HD0:
  FileReqPreset3 HD1 HD1:
  FileReqPreset4 RAM RAM:
  -The FileReqPreset refers to the four buttons that can be seen at the
   top of all LightWave requesters.  In this instance they are pointing
   to the wrong drives, so I need to change them to DH0 DH0: and DH1 DH1:

  ScenesDirectory 3D:Scenes
  ObjectsDirectory 3D:Objects
  HierarchiesDirectory 3D:Scenes
  SurfacesDirectory 3D:Surfaces
  ImagesDirectory 3D:Images
  OutputDirectory 3D:Images
  FramestoresDirectory 3D:Images
  MotionsDirectory 3D:Motions
  EnvelopesDirectory 3D:Envelopes
  PreviewsDirectory 3D:Previews
  -The 10 lines above tell LightWave where to look when you click on
   Scene, Objects, Surfaces, Images, Motions, Envelopes and Previews.
   Currently they are pointing to 'fake logical volume' called 3D:, this
   was created in the 'user-startup' file.  The basic install of LightWave
   however will be written as such:

   	ScenesDirectory DH1:Toaster/3D/Scenes
	ObjectsDirectory DH1:Toaster/3D/Objects
	HierarchiesDirectory DH1:Toaster/3D/Scenes
	SurfacesDirectory DH1:Toaster/3D/Surfaces
	ImagesDirectory DH1:Toaster/3D/Images
	OutputDirectory DH1:Toaster/3D/Images
	FramestoresDirectory DH1:Toaster/3D/Images
	MotionsDirectory DH1:Toaster/3D/Motions
	EnvelopesDirectory DH1:Toaster/3D/Envelopes
	PreviewsDirectory DH1:Toaster/3D/Previews 

  StatusFilename (none)
  -Back when we did not have powerful computers and render farms were 
   common this was an option used for render farm software.

  DefaultTension 0.000000
  -Changing this can cause any generated keyframe to have tension value
   set to this number (-1 to 1), useful if you do a lot of logo work.

  DefaultSegmentMemory 2200000
  -(Camera panel) This number is used to how much segement memory 
   LightWave will use when rendering images.  It is set quite low due to
   Amigas not having much memory back in the day but with most Amigas 
   having at least 64mb or more you can set this to a higher number.

  DefaultZoomFactor 3.200000
  -Default setting for camera lens when a new scene is started, the 
   default creates a 24mm lens.

  DefaultOverlay 0
  -This interestingly is a feature that was requested by the seaQuest
   animators, the value will determine if LightWave's Data Overlay option 
   will be on (1) or off (0) by default.  If the setting is on, you will 
   be asked if you want the scene name put into the Data Overlay label.

  FrameEndBeep 0
  -Similar to DataOverlay, 0 will be the default Frame End Beep (scene
   panel) off whenver you start LightWave and 1 will default it on.

  RenderDisplayDevice 0
  -Each time you exit LightWave the current settings will be written.
   Essentially it determines what the Render Display will be set to the
   next time you run LightWave.  The options are: None (0), Toaster (1)
   6-bit HAM (2), 8-bit HAM (3) and Picasso II (4).  

  RecordSetup1 (none)
  RecordSetup2 (none)
  RecordCommand (none)
  RecordDelay 0.000000
  FirstFrameDelay 0.000000
  -Upon exiting LightWave the five lines above are written, they refer to
   text entered for Record Setup 1, Record Setup 2, Record Command, Frame
   Record Delay and Extra First Delay.  These are useful when recording by
   single frame to video device.

  DefaultLayoutGrid 4
  -This is not written by LightWave but it sets the default settings for
   Layout Grid, the options being Off (0) to 16x16 (8).

  AutoKeyAdjust 0
  -Affecting the Auto Key Adjust button in the Options Panel, 0 is the 
   button is off and 1 means the button is turned on.  When you modify 
   anything on a keyframe it will automatically create a new keyframe.
   Great for creating a still image but can wreck havok if you are doing
   an animation.

  ExpertMode 0
  -A redundant feature, however when it was turned off (0) you would be
   warned each time you selected a raytracing button, telling you that it
   would take a long time to render.

  As you can see the LW-config file offers a lot of customisation, 
  allowing you to setup LightWave how you want it.  Next time we will
  look at the MOD-config file and see how we can customise the Modeler.                      
@endnode  

@node brilliance101 "Brilliance 101 - Reflection and Gradient"
@toc guides
============================================================================
 	     @{b}Brilliance 101 Part 5@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

  @{b}Stencils Galore!@{ub}
  Hello and welcome back to another installment of the Brilliance 101
  tutorial series, this issue we will be looking at using the Stencil
  tool in Brilliance.  First let's answer the question, 'Why would you
  want to use a stencil in Brilliance?', well Stencils provide an easy
  way to mask off designated areas of your workspace or screen to prevent
  them from being painted over.  Sounds pretty neat right?  Before we
  start please make sure you are in the HAM version of Brilliance, the
  creation of a stencil mask differs slightly from the Register mode so
  we will start with the HAM version of Brilliance for this tutorial.

  Go to the Gradient menu and choose gradient 2, we choose this one as it
  has a large colour pallete and will help in highlightin Variance.  Set
  Spread to 10 or higher, select Filled Rectangle tool and then choose
  Hightlight fromthe Draw Modes menu and drag out a large rectangle on
  your work screen.  It is not important but you need to set the 
  highlight position, anywhere is fine but for this tutorial we just put
  it in the middle of the box.

  Next bring up the Stencil menu remembering to right mouse click on the
  Stencil tool.  We won't need any other tools at the moment so you 
  close the rest of the tools.  Now that you are in the Stencil tool 
  click on the Select button, you will notice the pointer will turn into
  an eyedropper.  From here find the red area of the box that you drew
  out, click on the reddest part.  Now that you have finished that part
  check the Variance settings are all set to 10.  The manual explains
  Varience best so I will use it's explanation:

  "Variance sets the acceptable range of colours, on either side of the 
  selected colour, that will be incorporated into the mask."

  The Variance settings refer to the Hue, Sauration and Value and we 
  have set them at 10% which is pretty tight range, have a play around
  with the settings later on to see the different Varience settings
  will have on yor Stencil.

  For now let's do a quick test, click on Draw Modes and double check
  that 'Color' is selected.  Select black from the pallete and choosem 
  the Filled Rectangle tool again, draw out a black box completely 
  covering the gradient box.  You will see right away that only the red
  part of the box shows up, congratulations you have done your first 
  Stencil Mask in Brilliance.

  @{b}Next Step@{ub}
  If you haven't done so yet, press U on the keyboard or click on UNDO
  to remove the black box covering your gradient box.  Go back to the 
  Stencil Tool box and set the 'Variance' to 20, click on 'Select' and
  choose the same red colour again.  Click on 'Colors' in the 'Stencil
  Mask' tool, then draw the black box over your gradient box again, 
  you will notice that there are more colours now showing.  The Variance
  settings are much more useful when using the HAM version of Brilliance
  due to more colours being available.

  So far we have used the Stencil in Replace mode, which means that we 
  have been creating a new stencil each time.  If you have a quick 
  look at the Stencil tool you will see there are three options:

	Replace
	Add
	Subtract

  It is possible to use the Add mode to include area of different hues
  or the Replace mode to remove colours from the stencil mask.  But to
  move on, press U or click on UNDO again and let's try one more trick
  with the Stencil tool for this part.  Once you are back in the Stencil
  toolbar click on 'Invert', drag another black box and you will see this
  time only the red colour is removed with the other colours remaing.

  One thing to note is that because we are working in HAM mode the 
  stencil works with a much wider range of colours instead of a single
  colour, as such the active stencil colours are not shown.  In the
  register version of Brilliance the stencil colours are shown with an
  oval.

  Undo the black box again and delete the stencil mask by clicking on
  'Delete' in the Stencil menu.  Now clukc on 'Lasso', locate the area
  that contains the colours you want to isolate, draw a line around 
  them.  To see which colours became part ofthe mask, draw a black box
  over the gradient.

  So far we have looked at how to create a stencil mask from the colours
  that are already on the screen.  However Brilliance also allows you to
  easily draw the stencil mask onto the screen.  Let's take a look at
  that next.

  @{b}Drawing a Stencil@{ub}
  First you will need to delete your stencil, like before.  After you 
  have done that right mouse click on the 'Draw Mode' tool to bring it
  up and click on 'Stencil'.  Choose a filled draw such as a 'Filled
  Rectangle' or 'Filled Shape', draw any shape, maybe your name if it
  is not too long.  Remember if you want to remove a part of your 
  stencil you can do this by holding down the right mouse button and 
  drawing your desired shape.  Once you have drawn your stencil, choose
  'Color' in the 'Draw Mode' tool and once again select the colour black
  and draw a box over your entire gradient.  This time you should see
  only your stencil appear filled with the gradient.  Very easy isn't it?

  Thank you for having joined me on this Brilliance tutorial, good luck
  with your artwork and if you have some finished pieces please send them
  into the Amiga Art Contest 2022, you can find more at: 

				www.amigaartwork.com

  Until next time, keep creating and see you in the October issue for our
  next Brilliance installment.    
@endnode           		   

@node arexxstems "ARexx Stems as Mock Data"
@toc guides
============================================================================
       @{b}Stems as Mock Data Structures in REXX@{ub} - by: @{"Carl Svensson" link carlsvensson}
============================================================================

/**************************************************************************/

                Stems as mock data structures in REXX
             ============================================
                  An experimental "Tutorial as Code"
               (c) 2021 @{"Carl Svensson" link carlsvensson} | www.datagubbe.se
           Tested in ARexx 1.15, Regina REXX 3.6, BRexx 2.1.9

 The REXX language was invented at IBM by Mike Cowlishaw and has since
 been ported from IBM's mainframes to many various platforms, including DOS
 and OS/2. In 1987 it was ported to the Amiga range of computers (as ARexx)
 by William S. Hawes. Today, REXX is available on a multitude of platforms
 thanks to the portable interpreters Regina and BRexx.

 REXX itself has no particular data structures as supplied in modern
 scripting languages such as JavaScript and Python. It provides variables
 and a single stack, but by using what could be described as "syntactic
 sugar" for manipulating the internal symbol table, it enables something
 called stems and compound variables.

 The aim of this tutorial is not to introduce the basics of the REXX
 language, but rather to explain a few concepts that are, AFAIK, unique to
 the REXX family of languages.

 Even though the tutorial has a stupendously pretentious name, the
 hope is that it will be instructive enough to explain how combining
 stems, subroutines and evaluation of strings as code can substitute the
 need for many other language constructs that are not immediately available
 in REXX.

 This tutorial comes with ABSOLUTELY NO WARRANTY and is licensed under
 the CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license.
 For details, see https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/

***************************************************************************/


/* ====================================================================== */
/*                     Variables and the symbol table.                    */
/* ====================================================================== */

say foobar                     /* An uninitialized symbol will evaluate   */
                               /* to an uppercase string. This will print */
                               /* FOOBAR, as will henceforth be denoted   */
                               /* by the arrow "--->" in this tutorial:   */
                               /* ---> FOOBAR                             */

foobar = 42                    /* Initialize the variable foobar to       */
                               /* create an entry in the symbol table.    */

say foobar                     /* ---> 42                                 */

drop foobar                    /* Remove the variable from the            */
                               /* symbol table.                           */

say foobar                     /* ---> FOOBAR                             */


/* ====================================================================== */
/*                Stems, compounds and the symbol table.                  */
/* ====================================================================== */

mystem. = 31337                /* The stem mystem. is initialized         */
                               /* with the default value 31337.           */
                               /* Stems are not like lists or arrays, but */
                               /* rather syntactic sugar for working with */
                               /* the REXX symbol table - I.E., declaring */
                               /* variables.                              */
                               /* As such, they can be used to implement  */
                               /* or at least approximate the behavior of */
                               /* common structures in other languages.   */

say mystem.                    /* ---> 31337                              */
                               /* The value of mystem. itself is its      */
                               /* default value.                          */

say mystem.1                   /* ---> 31337                              */
                               /* The compound variable mystem.1          */
                               /* is now initialized to the stem's        */
                               /* default value. The stem's name is       */
                               /* mystem. and the 'index', 1, is called   */
                               /* a 'tail' in REXX.                       */

mystem.2 = 3                   /* Initialize compound variable mystem.2   */
                               /* with the value 3. All new compounds     */
                               /* get new individual entries in REXX's    */
                               /* symbol table.                           */

say mystem.2                   /* ---> 3                                  */

say mystem.1 + mystem.2        /* ---> 31340                              */

drop mystem.1                  /* Drop the compound mystem.1              */
                               /* from the symbol table.                  */

say mystem.1                   /* In ARexx and Regina REXX, this will     */
                               /* result in a completely dropped symbol,  */
                               /* which will evaluate to an uppercase     */
                               /* string:                                 */
                               /* ---> MYSTEM.1                           */
                               /* In BRexx it will result in reverting to */
                               /* the stem's default value:               */
                               /* ---> 31337                              */
                               /* This tutorial remains agnostic as to    */
                               /* which behavior is "correct".            */

mystem.foo = "Hello"           /* Compounds can be of any type            */
                               /* both in name and value, regardless      */
                               /* of the stem default. We can write       */
                               /* foo in lowercase for convenience,       */
                               /* but resolution will really be in        */
                               /* uppercase.                              */

say mystem.foo                 /* ---> Hello                              */

tail = "FOO"                   /* Initialize a normal string variable     */
                               /* intended for tail substitution.         */
                               /* Note the uppercase!                     */

say mystem.tail                /* ---> Hello                              */
                               /* REXX resolves the value of the          */
                               /* tail before resolving the compound,     */
                               /* meaning we can dynamically access       */
                               /* arbitrary tails using a variable.       */
                               /* This is called tail substitution.       */

tail = foo                     /* Since uninitialized symbols evaluate    */
                               /* to uppercase strings, we can assign an  */
                               /* unquoted value to a variable we want to */
                               /* use for tail substitution.              */

say tail                       /* ---> FOO                                */
say mystem.tail                /* ---> Hello                              */

mystem.bar = 12                /* Here we create a clash:                 */
bar = "FOO"                    /* The tail BAR contains the value 12,     */
                               /* but we assign the value FOO to the      */
                               /* variable BAR.                           */

say mystem.bar                 /* ---> Hello                              */
                               /* REXX tail substitutes BAR with 'FOO',   */
                               /* giving us the value for MYSTEM.FOO.     */

drop bar                       /* Let's remove BAR from the symbol table. */
say mystem.bar                 /* ---> 12                                 */
                               /* Since we dropped BAR, MYSTEM.BAR now    */
                               /* resolves to the intended value.         */

newstem. = mystem.             /* It's not possible to create a copy of   */
                               /* or reference to a stem by assignment.   */
                               /* In this assignment, we simply create a  */
                               /* newstem. stem with the default value of */
                               /* 31337, since that's the actual value of */
                               /* mystem.                                 */
say newstem.foo                /* ---> 31337                              */
newstem.foo = "Baz!"           /* This will only affect newstem.          */
say newstem.foo                /* ---> Baz!                               */
say mystem.foo                 /* ---> Hello                              */
newstem.foo = mystem.foo       /* All values we wish to retain must be    */
                               /* copied explicitly. Remember, a compound */
                               /* will get a unique entry in the symbol   */
                               /* table!                                  */
say newstem.foo                /* --> Hello                               */

x = 31; y = 13; z = 73         /* Tails can be chained to create multi-   */
coords.x.y.z = 23              /* dimensional stems.                      */
say coords.x.y.z               /* ---> 23                                 */
say coords.31.13.73            /* ---> 23                                 */

array.0 = 0                    /* A common pattern in REXX is to store    */
                               /* the number of stem elements in tail 0.  */

do i = 1 to 5                  /* When populating a stem intended for use */
  array.i = "I am "i"!"        /* as an array, we must keep track of the  */ 
  array.0 = i                  /* <=== element count                      */
end                            /* ourselves.                              */

say array.0                    /* ---> 5                                  */

do i = 1 to array.0
  say array.i                  /* ---> I am 1! ... I am 5!                */
end

/* ====================================================================== */
/*                              Interpret.                                */
/* ====================================================================== */

interpret "say 'Hello!'"      /* ---> Hello!                              */
                              /* INTERPRET allows for the interpretation  */
                              /* of an arbitrary string as REXX code,     */
                              /* much like eval() in JavaScript.          */

interpret "say array.1"       /* ---> I am 1!                             */
                              /* The global scope is accessible.          */

interpret "mystem.baz = 10"   /* The global scope can be manipulated.     */
say mystem.baz                /* ---> 10                                  */

anum = 1                      /* As evident from these lines and the ones */
interpret "bnum = 2"          /* just above, we can manipulate both       */
                              /* normal and compound variables.           */
interpret "say anum + bnum"   /* ---> 3                                   */
say bnum                      /* ---> 2                                   */

stem = "mystem"               /* We can also use INTERPRET to dynamically */
tail = "foo"                  /* access compounds based on the values of  */
                              /* variables:                               */
interpret "say "stem"."tail   /* ---> Hello                               */

/* ====================================================================== */
/*                         Labels and procedures.                         */
/* ====================================================================== */

my_label:                      /* A label. Without any special control    */
                               /* flow, this will simply be a no-op and   */
                               /* the code following it will execute      */
                               /* normally, just like a label in C.       */

say "Below my_label."          /* ---> Below my_label.                    */

call skip_here                 /* Here we call the label skip_here, as    */
                               /* declared below.                         */

say "Between call and label."  /* This line will not be executed.         */

skip_here:                     /* The label called above.                 */
say "We are now here!"         /* ---> We are now here!                   */

call subroutine                /* Call the label "subroutine" defined     */
                               /* below.                                  */
                               /* ---> I can access mystem:               */
                               /*      Hello                              */

call myproc                    /* Call the label "myproc" defined below.  */
                               /* ---> I can access array:                */
                               /*      I am 1!                            */
                               /*      But not mystem:                    */
                               /*      MYSTEM.FOO                         */

say myfunc("a string")         /* Invoke the label "myfunc" defined below */
                               /* as a function.                          */
                               /* ---> I received a string                */

idx = arrayfunc("New item")    /* Invoke the function "arrayfunc" defined */
                               /* below and store the return value.       */
say array.idx                  /* ---> New item                           */

idx = arrpush(array, "Pushed") /* Invoke the function "arrpush" defined   */
                               /* below.                                  */
                               /* We use the fact that REXX will treat    */
                               /* uninitialized variables as uppercase    */
                               /* strings to mock the use of a stem as a  */
                               /* function argument.                      */
say array.idx                  /* ---> Pushed                             */

call arrcopy array, new_array  /* Call the label "arrcopy" defined        */
                               /* below, to copy the contents of array to */
                               /* new_array. Note that there's no need to */
                               /* first declare the target stem, it will  */
                               /* be initialized by our function if it    */
                               /* doesn't exist.                          */

do i = 1 to new_array.0        /* Here we loop over the contents of our   */
  say "New: "new_array.i       /* new_array stem and print the values.    */
end                            /* ---> New: I am 1!                       */
                               /*      New: I am 2!                       */
                               /*      New: I am 3!                       */
                               /*      New: I am 4!                       */
                               /*      New: I am 5!                       */
                               /*      New: New item                      */
                               /*      New: Pushed                        */



exit                           /* Labels can also be used to declare      */
                               /* subroutines and procedures, but since   */
                               /* we don't want to execute them within    */
                               /* the normal program flow, we must EXIT   */
                               /* the program flow before declaring them, */
                               /* or the interpreter will execute them    */
                               /* just like with "my_label" above.        */


/* ====================================================================== */
/*                   subroutine: A label as a subroutine                  */
/* ====================================================================== */
subroutine:                    /* This label can be described as a        */
                               /* subroutine and will have access to the  */
                               /* full symbol scope of the script.        */
  say "I can access mystem:"
  say mystem.foo
return                         /* Return to the call statement            */


/* ====================================================================== */
/*                   myproc: A locally scoped procedure                   */
/* ====================================================================== */
myproc:                        /* This label will be treated as a         */
                               /* procedure, a subroutine with a local    */
                               /* scope that can be augmented using the   */
                               /* EXPOSE keyword, to expose arbitrary     */
                               /* values from the global scope.           */

  procedure expose array.      /* PROCEDURE tells REXX that we want a     */
                               /* local scope. EXPOSE is used to "expose" */
                               /* desired values from the global scope,   */
                               /* which lets us access them from our      */
                               /* local scope.                            */

  say "I can access array:"
  say array.1                  /* ---> I am 1!                            */
  say "But not mystem:"
  say mystem.foo               /* ---> MYSTEM.FOO                         */
return

/* ====================================================================== */
/*                        myfunc: Returning a value                       */
/* ====================================================================== */
myfunc:                        /* To create a function, we can accept     */
                               /* arguments using PARSE ARG and return    */
                               /* a value to the caller.                  */
  parse arg str_a
  new_str = "I received "str_a
return new_str


/* ====================================================================== */
/*    arrayfunc: Add a value to a stem and return the new item count      */
/* ====================================================================== */
arrayfunc:                     /* Let's create a locally scoped function. */

  procedure expose array.      /* Because stems are a kind of sugar for   */
                               /* working with the symbol table, we       */
                               /* cannot pass a stem as an argument to a  */
                               /* function. To be able to work with it,   */
                               /* we must access it in the global symbol  */
                               /* table just like any other variable.     */

  parse arg new_val            /* Accept one argument                     */

  new_count = array.0 + 1      /* Calculate our new item count.           */

  array.new_count = new_val    /* Add our new value to the array.         */

  array.0 = new_count          /* Update the item count.                  */

return new_count               /* Return the new item count.              */


/* ====================================================================== */
/*               arrpush: Pushing an item to a stem-as-array              */
/* ====================================================================== */
arrpush:                       /* Now things are getting interesting!     */
                               /* In this function with access to the     */
                               /* global scope, we accept the name of     */
                               /* an arbitrary stem intended for use as   */
                               /* an array, and push values onto it using */
                               /* the INTERPRET instruction.              */

  parse arg stem_name, push_val     /* Our arguments: the stem's name and */
                                    /* the value to push.                 */

  interpret stem_name".0 = "stem_name".0 + 1"  /* Assume the item count   */
                                               /* is in tail 0 and        */
                                               /* increment it.           */

  interpret "new_count = "stem_name".0"  /* Store the new item count in a */
                                         /* variable for use below.       */

  interpret stem_name"."new_count" = '"push_val"'"  /* Assign a value to  */
                                                    /* the new item.      */

return new_count               /* Return the new item count.              */


/* ====================================================================== */
/*                arrcopy: Create a copy of a stem-as-array               */
/* ====================================================================== */
arrcopy:                       /* To copy an arbitrary array stem, we     */
                               /* create a subroutine that accepts two    */
                               /* stem names, the source and the target.  */

  parse arg arr_source, arr_target        /* Our args, source and target. */

  interpret "drop "arr_target"."             /* Drop the target to ensure */
                                             /* it's empty. If it doesn't */
                                             /* exist, this will not      */
                                             /* cause an error.           */

  interpret "source_count = "arr_source".0"  /* Assume the item count is  */
                                             /* in tail 0 and store it in */
                                             /* a variable for use below. */

  do i = 1 to source_count                       /* Loop over the source. */

    interpret arr_target"."i" = "arr_source"."i  /* Copy the value from   */
                                                 /* source to target.     */
  end

  interpret arr_target".0 = "source_count        /* Set the target's item */
                                                 /* counter.              */
return

/* ========================== End of tutorial. ========================== */

@endnode               

@node floppygotek "Floppy Disks and You"
@toc guides
============================================================================
       @{b}Floppy Disks and You@{ub} - by: @{"Ivan Sorensen" link ivansorensen}
============================================================================

  @{b}Floppy disks and you@{ub}
  To get anything out of a computer you of course need to software into it
  first and the default way of doing this has always been the floppy disk: 
  Every Amiga comes with one and when Commodore was around it was the way 
  software was distributed, even if you intended to run it off a hard 
  drive.

  For a while, it seemed like floppies were becoming obsolete: CD ROM 
  became the way for magazines to distribute huge collections of software 
  and the internet allowed things to be downloaded directly on to your 
  machine. With the rise of WHDLoad, you could even forego floppy disks 
  completely for daily games playing.

  However, in the modern age it seems that the floppy has made a sort of 
  return. A lot of new Amiga games are coming out and while many are 
  intended to just be installed directly, some are distributed in ADF 
  format and while there are ways to mount disk images to RAD, this isnt 
  practical for multiple disk games.

  So after many years of neglecting those old drives, we have to dust them 
  off again and that raises the question of replacing them. I stuck with my 
  old drive for years out of habit, but eventually gave in and got a Gotek 
  floppy drive emulator. There are other versions of these out there, but 
  the Gotek is the one I have experience with.
   
  What it does is plug into the Amiga using the normal floppy cable. You 
  then load disk images on to a USB stick and plug it into the drive. The 
  Amiga then reads the ADF exactly as if it was a real disk.
   
  The USB stick can hold multiple files, allowing you to swap disks by 
  clicking the physical buttons on the front of the drive. You do have to 
  memorize or write down what ADFs you have on the stick, but it is rather 
  convenient to work with. It is also quiet and you donât have to worry 
  about whether a copy protection scheme is going to strangle your disk 
  drive. 

  As far as the Amiga is concerned, it is a genuine disk running off of a 
  genuine drive so compatibility is very high. I am sure that some edge 
  case must exist, but so far it has run everything I have tried to load on 
  it. Do note that since it is accurate in terms of emulation, that also 
  means speed: The game loads in the time it would take it to actually load 
  from disk. If you are used to hard drive games and WHDLoad, it can be a 
  bit of a crude reminder.

  On the physical side of things there are some different configurations 
  you can get. The standard Gotek version seems to be built to fit in a PC 
  style case and will NOT fit smoothly in an Amiga wedge case: You will 
  need to modify your case or trail the cable out the back of the machine 
  and use the drive on its own. I have seen modified Goteks specifically 
  for Amiga usage though. I assume if you have a big box machine, you will 
  be fine.

  Other than the difficulty with the physical case (I eventually resolved 
  to just leave my case slightly open, since I use an external keyboard 
  anyway) installation was simple: Just remove the old drive and plug the 
  cables right into the new one. There is no software needed on the Amiga: 
  As far as the computer is concerned, it really is just a floppy drive. 
  The one I purchased came with Amiga specific firmware already loaded, but 
  these devices are highly configurable. 

  Are there any reasons to retain your original drives? I am hard pressed 
  to think of one other than authenticity and the desire to keep a given 
  machine in original configuration (or if your hobby has a strict only 
  Commodore era hardware philosophy). 
  For the average modern user, the Gotek not only is more reliable (and 
  quiet!) than an old drive, it also makes it much easier to actually USE 
  your machine. As anyone who have bought an Amiga 500 can attest to: Its 
  all fun and games until you realize you have no way to actually get 
  software on to your new machine. The Gotek solves that problem: ¨You can 
  simply download disk images from the internet, put them on a cheap USB 
  stick and be up and running on your real hardware. 

  If you have held off, I highly encourage you to give floppy drive 
  emulators a look. I think you will be pleasantly surprised at how 
  convenient they really are.
@endnode

@node a1200fpu "A1200 Internal FPU Installation"
@toc guides
============================================================================
	   @{b}Internal FPU on A1200@{ub} - by: @{"Chris Edwards" link chrisedwards} & @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

  @{b}Chris Edwards Presents@{ub}
  If you have one of the Terrible Fire accelerator boards for your Amiga, 
  you already know how great they are.  However there is one thing that is
  not a deal breaker but can be a little bit of an issue for users, and 
  that is the lack of an FPU.  Now before you start shouting at me that the
  majority of Amiga software does not require an FPU and it is a waste of
  time and effort, let me explain a bit more.  For the average user, yes, 
  an FPU is generally not needed; if you play games, write music or do 
  pixel art, then the FPU is simply not an issue.  

  However, if you are a power user and by that I mean a person who does 3D 
  rendering or image processing then an FPU can range from being helpful to 
  essential.  An example are the TF12060 users who want to run LightWave 
  4.0, you have the power of the LC060 but LW4.0 requires an Amiga with an 
  FPU to run, no FPU no LW4.0.

  Sadly there is no space on the board to add an FPU so the ever creative 
  Chris Edwards post peaked my interest.  He has posted a very useful video 
  detailing how to install an FPU directly to the A1200 motherboard 
  allowing you to use your, for example, TF1260 with an onboard FPU.  I 
  contacted Chris and he kindly agreed to let WhatIFF? publish his video in
  text form.  What follows is a rough transcript of his video.

  On the A1200 motherboard there is a blank spot in U0, this is the missing
  FPU slot, you have two options 1) solder the FPU directly to the 
  motherboard or 2) attach a PLCC IC socket to the motherboard.  Chris chose
  option 2.  To start with the sockets are still readily available online, 
  but the FPUs ... not as much as they once were, so you might need to 
  search a bit online.  Once you have your socket and FPU, the first thing
  you will need to do is pop out the wafer in the middle of the socket.  

  @{b}But ... @{ub}
  At this point, Chris mentions that others might object since the A1200 
  motherboard does not have a crystal to control the speed of the FPU.  
  Here he points out that the FPU is on the motherboard as such it is 
  controlled by the onboard EC020 and runs at 14mhz, thus the FPU will 
  run at 14mhz.  Now it is not going to be as fast as your accelerator 
  board but this is not the objective of the task, what we are looking to 
  do is give the A1200 FPU functionality so that it can run software that 
  would otherwise not run without the FPU.

  Before beginning to solder he recommends visiting www.amigapcb.org to 
  help with circuit tracing, you do need to know your motherboard revision 
  though.  His motherboard is a 1D1 the most common board, watching the 
  video it seemed a relatively straightforward task however, if you have 
  not done any soldering beforehand you might want to get someone else 
  with more experience to add the socket.  It took Chris about 30 minutes 
  from start to finish.  He proceeded to do some software checks and 
  incredibly the FPU was recognised alongside the TF1230.  When he tried 
  to run software that requires an FPU there were no issues, the TF1230 
  was used as the main CPU and the onboard FPU was recognised allowing 
  FPU-specific software to run.  His video can be found here:

			https://youtu.be/pUtf2D9IAco

  Overall it is a very interesting video and something that if I had more 
  experience with soldering would try.  Chris does recommend doing some 
  practice soldering on old hardware but compared to some of the other 
  soldering I have seen, this one is not too difficult looking.  As it 
  stands I will still be asking my local Amiga hardware guy to add the 
  socket for me, I have not had much luck with soldering in the past and
  do not want to damage my A1200.  It is good to know that this is 
  possible and relatively easy and cheap, if you try this yourself let us
  know how you got along and tell us what you were using the FPU for.
@endnode               

