@node littlethings "Little Things That Made The Amiga Great"
@toc articles
============================================================================
     @{b}Little Things That Made The Amiga Great - by: @{"Carl Svensson" link carlsvensson}
============================================================================

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}
  To most people, the Amiga is probably synonymous with the Amiga 500 and
  that machine was, above all, a video game: something into which you 
  plonked 3.5" floppy disks that transported you to strange, wonderful 
  worlds and hours of fun. To this group, the gamers, the operating 
  system wasn't important. They probably booted Workbench 1.3 only once, 
  took a good look at the garish blue and orange interface, and decided 
  that enough was enough, before going back to blasting enemies in 
  Silkworm.

  And why not? The machine was great for games. There are tons of great 
  texts about the groundbreaking audio and video capabilities of the 
  Amiga.

  This text is not one of those.

  This text is about the later versions of AmigaOS produced by Commodore,
  from 2.0 to 3.1. While these newer versions (with majors released in 
  1990 and 1992, respectively) certainly carried the Amiga heritage with 
  pride and were - mostly - backwards compatible, the advent of AmigaOS 
  2.0 marked a paradigm shift. The shift is best symbolized by the fact 
  that AmigaBASIC - the ubiquitous and mandatory language of any 
  self-respecting eighties home computer - was ditched and replaced by 
  ARexx, a professional scripting language without any kind of graphics 
  or sound features whatsoever.

  This paradigm shift is also why so many of us who had the good fortune 
  to come across those versions clung to the Amiga so desperately. A lot 
  of us stuck with it well into the late nineties, years after 
  Commodore's demise. And we were fierce: if you think Apple fanboys are 
  annoying today, be very happy you didn't meet an Amiga zealot in 1995. 
  Things got personal quickly. It was downright ugly.

  I still think there were some grounds for our fanaticism, though.

  In a time when home PC:s were single tasking DOS boxes with 8-character 
  file names and Ataris and Macs were single tasking GUI boxes, hampering 
  any hacker with their glaring lack of a CLI, the Amiga was a champion 
  of both worlds: It combined the CLI and GUI, leveraging both their 
  strengths. But there was more to it than that, something that's hard to 
  convey in so many words.

  Many a time have I come across exasperated Amiga users who, on some 
  online forum, try to explain the greatness of the Amiga's operating 
  system in a few short sentences. It often, quite understandably, boils 
  down to something akin to "It's like UNIX", which I always think is 
  unfair to both of the systems.

  Sure, it was an early multitasking system with a capable command line. 
  At the same time, it was also a mature and coherent desktop environment 
  with levels of user-friendliness much more like today's MacOS X than 
  any traditional UNIX. But, contrary to today's MacOS, it never 
  mollycoddled the end user. It opened the machine up, rather than 
  closing certain parts off.

  Unlike UNIX, AmigaOS is a system designed for home computer use, 
  lacking a lot of what makes UNIX so popular: memory protection, 
  multi-user support, source code portability and built-in networking 
  support.

  They're very much alike in one aspect, though. Like UNIX, the Amiga's 
  operating system is a collection of a lot of little strokes of genius 
  that come together to make it bigger than the sum of its parts.

  I invite you to explore this ingenuity with me. But first, let's get 
  the terminology sorted.

  @{b}Jargon buster@{ub}
  The Amiga's operating system has been called a lot of things by a lot 
  of people because it consists of many components that different types 
  of users interacted more or less with. Let me try to clear things up 
  a bit:

  @{b}AmigaOS@{ub}
  Commodore didn't call the operating system as a whole "AmigaOS" until 
  the release of version 3.1 in 1994, the year they went defunct. And 
  even then, it was mostly printed on the box it came in - nothing in the
  OS calls itself AmigaOS. It's still a useful umbrella term for all of 
  the components below.

  @{b}Kickstart@{ub}
  This is basically the firmware of the Amiga, residing in the ROM chip.
  On version 2.0 and up, the ROM chip was 512 kB large and contained not
  only code for self-tests and bootstrapping but also quite sizable 
  portions of the other parts of AmigaOS.

  @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub}
  This is, roughly speaking, the command line interface, device drivers, 
  file system management and so on. It was originally based on TRIPOS, a 
  heritage that still shows to this day. (There are newer versions of 
  AmigaOS than 3.1, but this text will only cover the ones released by 
  Commodore.)

  @{b}Intuition@{ub}
  Best likened to a modern desktop compositor, Intuition handles screen 
  updates and manages windows. The custom sound and video chips in the 
  Amiga had mostly female names (Paula, Denise and later Alice), so I 
  suppose Intuition is a fitting name for an abstraction layer that lets 
  the OS interface with them.

  @{b}Workbench@{ub}
  This is often used interchangeably with "AmigaOS" but it's really the 
  name of just the desktop environment - which is a workbench, not a 
  desktop: Programs are called tools, folders a called drawers and 
  data files are called projects.

  @{b}Other terminology@{ub}

  @{b}Requesters@{ub}
  Not really a major part of the OS per se, a requester is the Amiga's 
  name for a dialog box. A "file requester" is a file selection dialog, 
  for example. I still often use this term to describe any dialog on 
  any platform, much to the confusion of friends and colleagues. Old 
  habits die hard.

  @{b}Devices@{ub}
  Devices, much like in UNIX, usually represent peripherals attached to 
  the computer, such as storage media, printers, etc. The Amiga has a 
  number of built-in devices that are automatically mounted, for example 
  the internal floppy drive, DF0: and the serial and parallel ports, 
  SER: and PAR: respectively. Other common devices are DF1:, the first 
  external floppy drive, DH0:, the common device name given to the 
  bootable hard drive partition, and CON:, the text console. There are 
  also devices that can't be mounted but only be accessed using 
  programming languages, such as timer.device which is used to 
  interface with hardware clocks.

  @{b}Volumes@{ub}
  Mounted devices (such as DF0, DF1, DH0) can contain a volume. In the 
  case of DH0:, a bootable hard drive partition, the volume is fixed and 
  is represented by the name of the partition, such as System: or Boot:. 
  If you insert the Deluxe Paint program disk into the internal floppy 
  drive, the current volume in device DF0: will be DPaint:.

  @{b}The RAM Disk@{ub}
  The Amiga always has a RAM disk ready for use and the device name is 
  always RAM:. No mounting, no third party software - it just sits there, 
  waiting. That's clever in its own right, but the really ingenious part 
  about it is that it's dynamically allocated. That means the size of the 
  RAM disk corresponds to the amount of free memory currently available 
  on the system, and that it never takes up more memory than is needed to 
  accommodate the files currently stored on it.

  A RAM disk might sound esoteric today, but in the days of slow 
  mechanical hard drives and floppy disks, it was a godsend for unpacking 
  archives, running test compiles and storing temporary working 
  documents.

  The downside is that every time you reboot your computer, all the 
  contents of the RAM disk are lost. Which brings us to...

  @{b}The RAD Disk@{ub}
  RAD, which (somehow) stands for Recoverable Ram Disk, is another 
  testament to the flexibility and ingenuity of AmigaOS. The RAD disk is 
  a fixed size RAM disk that can not only survive reboots but also 
  itself be booted from. It can be used as a small but extremely fast 
  mini hard drive, or for extracting disk images to, for checking out 
  their contents.

  @{b}Proportional scroll bars@{ub}
  A proportional scroll bar is a scroll bar that grows and shrinks to 
  reflect the size of the scrollable content it represents:

  Highlighting a feature like this might seem like a silly point to 
  make, because today all scroll bars are proportional. Not so in the 
  bad old days: Microsoft didn't implement them until Windows 95 and 
  Apple, as far as I know, didn't make the move until MacOS 9 in 1999. 
  In a time when computer mice had no scroll wheels, this was a nifty 
  feature indeed.

  @{b}The Text Editors@{ub}
  AmigaOS shipped with three different text editors: Ed, Edit and 
  MEmacs. The latter is a port of, you guessed it, Micro Emacs, and 
  will of course appeal to Emacs fans. The other two are sort of 
  curiously named: Edit is a line editor mostly resembling ed on 
  UNIX. The Amiga's Ed, on the other hand, is a full screen editor 
  with both mouse support and an extensive command language. Amiga Ed is 
  probably best likened with vi.

  All three of them are capable and powerful editors. Both MEmacs and Ed 
  make use of the Amiga's drop down GUI menus and feature support for 
  macros and extensive configuration.

  Ed's command mode is, as mentioned earlier, somewhat reminiscent of vi. 
  Consider the following examples:

  Change the next three occurrences of "data" to "gubbe":
  3 E/data/gubbe/

  Move to top of file, repeat (RP) replace of "data" with "gubbe" until 
  end of file:
  T; RP E/data/gubbe/

  Move to top of file, find all occurrences of "gubbe" and insert three 
  blank lines after every occurrence, repeat until end of file:
  T; RP (F /gubbe/; 3A//)

  Ed also has something called an ARexx port, which completely 
  intentionally leads us to...

  @{b}ARexx@{ub}
  ARexx is an improved and Amiga-ized version of IBM's REXX language. 
  It's a capable (albeit somewhat dated, these days) general-purpose 
  scripting language with excellent functions for easy string parsing.

  Through an interprocess communication interface, it can also act as 
  "glue" between various programs with so-called ARexx ports. For 
  example, if both your text editor and Desktop Publishing package 
  have ARexx ports, you can write a script for automatically inserting 
  the text you've just written in the editor into the desktop 
  publishing program by interfacing with them both using ARexx.

  Ed, the editor described above, exposes its command language through 
  its ARexx port, allowing users to create highly advanced text 
  processing scripts.

  @{b}No CD@{ub}
  While AmigaDOS does have a CD command, it's usually not needed. Any 
  command that evaluates to a valid path will automatically change the 
  current working directory to that path:

  1.System:> Work:Code/ARexx/WebServer
  1.Work:Code/ARexx/WebServer> _

  @{b}File Systems@{ub}
  OFS (Old File System) and FFS (Fast File System) are the Amiga's 
  native file systems. Thanks to the modular and ingenious nature of the 
  OS, the Amiga can, much like UNIX, handle an arbitrary amount of file 
  systems. Version 3.0 of the OS shipped with CrossDOS, a utility to 
  mount MS-DOS FAT volumes - but a lot of others have popped up as well, 
  from third-party native replacements for FFS to ports of for example 
  EXT2.

  @{b}Assigns@{ub}
  An assign is a kind of fake logical volume that can point to any path. 
  It's great for deep directory structures. Say you've got a current 
  programming project going in Work:Code/ARexx/WebServer. That's quite a 
  handful to type often. By creating an assign, 
  ASSIGN wserv: Work:Code/ARexx/WebServer, you can now access files and 
  CD to your project directory by referring to wserv: instead.

  An assign can also span several physical volumes. The Amiga's standard 
  assign where it looks for dynamic libraries is LIBS:, pointing at the 
  Libraries directory of the current boot volume. But what if you're 
  writing a new such library and don't want to litter your system 
  directory with your development versions of it while testing?

  Not to worry, you can ADD to any assign:

  1.System:> Assign LIBS: Work:Code/C/HTMLParseLibrary ADD

  AmigaOS will now look for dynamic library files in both paths!

  @{b}Libraries@{ub}
  Much like libraries in UNIX, this is a way of sharing common functions 
  between different programs. Amiga libraries are always dynamically 
  linked and yet, for some reason, there never seems to be any problems 
  with backwards compatibility. For an end user, things just generally 
  work.

  Commodore shipped AmigaOS with libraries for everything from 
  mathematical functions to something called ASL, used for creating file 
  and font requesters.

  @{b}ASL@{ub}
  The simplest way for a programmer to ask the user to pick a file or a 
  font is through the ASL library. Using a standardized API, a requester 
  (dialog) for saving or loading a document can be presented to the user. 
  The dialogs have functions for pattern matching and keyboard 
  navigation.

  Sadly, it doesn't stand for "Age, Sex, Location" but rather 
  "Amiga Standard Library."

  @{b}Datatypes@{ub}
  Datatypes are, in a sense, a bit like dynamic libraries for file 
  formats. Instead of relying solely on the capabilities of, say, a 
  graphics program to implement loaders for every conceivable file format
  if it supports Datatypes, it can load images of any format for which a 
  Datatype is installed in the system.

  This is a great way of future-proofing software, ensuring that even 
  older programs can load and display newer image formats. When the PNG 
  format was created in 1996, many Amiga programs made years earlier 
  could load those images through the use of a third-party PNG datatype 
  released as freeware.

  @{b}ReadArgs@{ub}
  While AmigaOS doesn't have online documentation like UNIX man pages, 
  it does have a standardized way for CLI programs to read arguments. 
  This is facilitated by the ReadArgs function, designed to help 
  programmers implement this way of reading arguments.

  The ? (question mark) argument always produces a list of a command's 
  arguments and their kind, and then awaits user input of said 
  arguments:

  1.System:> Delete ?
  FILE/M/A,ALL/S,QUIET/S,FORCE/S: _

  So what does this mean? It means that FILE can be multiple strings (/M) 
  and that it's a required argument (/A); ALL, QUIET and FORCE, 
  meanwhile, are boolean flags, or switches (/S).

  There are also patterns for keywords (/K), numbers (/N), and a handful 
  more. Once you get the hang of it, it's a very helpful reference system 
  for refreshing your memory, and the argument names tend to have 
  curiously sensible names.

  ReadArgs is refreshingly easy to implement in shell scripts, ensuring 
  conformity to standards even for the simplest of tasks.

  @{b}AmigaGuide@{ub}
  AmigaGuide is an early hypertext format, originally used by Commodore 
  for their official developer documentation, but delivered as a standard 
  component of AmigaOS 3.0 and up. It's simple compared to modern HTML: 
  it can't display inline images or play background sounds, but you can 
  create links to arbitrary files that are then displayed separately.

  It quickly became popular and before long, most freeware, shareware and 
  public domain programs came with AmigaGuide documentation.

  @{b}Installer@{ub}
  In the beginning, hard drive installation of programs was made using 
  shell scripts. Seeing the havoc wreaked by such scripts, Commodore 
  eventually created a standardized software installer. It's a brilliant 
  little tool for selecting installation paths, creating directories, 
  comparing file versions, copying files and modifying startup scripts.

  Pretty much all developers adopted this right away, including 
  PD/Freeware authors, much to the enjoyment of end-users. To this day, 
  installers for my crappy Amiga software remain the only really 
  meaningful thing I've coded in a purely functional language: 
  Installer scripts are written entirely in LISP.

  Because of the powerful nature of having a LISP dialect and easy 
  access to a subset of the Amiga's GUI widgets, the Installer has also 
  been used to create simple adventure games.

  @{b}Standardized File Structure@{ub}
  Every Amiga installation looks basically the same, especially where it 
  really matters. We've already covered shared libraries and their 
  residence in LIBS:. The same pattern is used for the rest of the system 
  files: Device drivers are always in DEVS:, file system drivers and 
  other low-level stuff in L:, AmigaDOS commands belong in C:, shell 
  scripts (including the bootup scripts, Startup-Sequence and 
  User-Startup) live in S:, typefaces are always in FONTS:, and so on.

  @{b}Resident programs@{ub}
  Some programs, most of them AmigaDOS commands, can be made resident - 
  that is, stored in memory for future use. This is useful to avoid 
  excess disk access when performing certain tasks.

  @{b}RequestChoice@{ub}
  AmigaDOS has a simple command for asking the user a Yes/No question, 
  called Ask. In version 3.0, Commodore introduced the commands 
  RequestChoice, for making a multiple-choice GUI requester and 
  RequestFile, for opening a file requester. A nice example of how 
  integrated the GUI and CLI environments are on AmigaOS.

  @{b}.info Files@{ub}
  A bit like with MacOS X, if you give a disk to an enthusiastic Amiga 
  novice and ask to have a few files copied onto it, you'll probably 
  find it littered with strange files that serve no apparent purpose. 
  They always have the same name as another file, but end with ".info".

  These are the Amiga's icon files, containing not only the actual icon 
  image, but also a bit of metadata. For a data file, that can be what 
  program to open the file with, which means that if you double click a 
  picture created with, say, Deluxe Paint, then Deluxe Paint will be 
  started and then load the picture in question. This is called the 
  file's "default tool".

  The .info files also contained positional information: the desired 
  coordinates of the icon within its parent window. For drawer 
  (directory) icons, it also stored the size and position of the 
  window opened to display their contents.

  Other noteworthy metadata is represented by the Tool Types, which can 
  be described as settings or arguments for a program. For example, such 
  a tool type can be used to control if Deluxe Paint should display the 
  coordinates for the mouse pointer's current position.

  A system with stand-alone icon files might seem odd today, but instead 
  of having centralized icon storage or embedding the icons into the 
  binaries, this method meant that tooltypes, default programs and 
  positional information could easily be transferred between systems. It 
  also gave the users freedom to modify or even draw new program icons or 
  delete them completely if they wanted to save disk space.

  Several beautiful icon sets were released as third-party shareware, 
  most notably Magic Workbench.

  @{b}Closing words@{ub}
  While certainly not a UNIX clone, the Amiga was still a great 
  preparatory platform for tackling other operating systems further on. 
  When I first stumbled across Linux (and other *nixes) in 1995, a lot of 
  stuff instinctively made sense to me. I easily drew parallels to 
  AmigaOS and was already familiar with a lot of the concepts: devices, 
  mounting, task priorities, shell scripts and scripting languages, 
  Emacs and much more. And as much as I enjoy UNIX today, it's when I sit 
  down in front of an Amiga that I truly feel at home and in control.

  I hope this text has given you some insight into what made the Amiga 
  great. There are of course many more things, but these are a few that 
  have stayed with me. Some concepts, like Datatypes, are still unique to 
  the Amiga and would be an interesting and useful addition to an 
  operating system even today.

  And remember - Only Amiga makes it possible!
@endnode

@node realamiga "Authenticity, the Amiga and you"
@toc articles
============================================================================
		@{b}Authenticity, the Amiga and You@{ub} - by: @{"Ivan Sorensen" link ivansorensen}
============================================================================

  @{b}Authenticity, the Amiga and you@{ub}
  Whenever retro-enthusiasts are discussing ways to interact with old 
  software, you inevitably get the discussion about what is authentic: 
  Is emulation authentic? Is a Raspberry Pi in an Amiga case authentic? 
  What about Morph OS or OS4? What about an FPGA system? Surely, an 
  actual Amiga is authentic right?

  Now first and foremost I want to preface this by saying that 
  authenticity ultimately depends on what specific things you value and 
  whether it is important at all is ultimately up to the end user. The 
  Amiga fan base has people who love the hardware and people who love 
  the software and they are not always the same people.
 
  But that doesn't mean we can't stop and take stock of the situation 
  and maybe try to explore the topic a little bit. Maybe we can then all
  get a better understand of each other and even ourselves?

  On the surface it appears to be simple enough: An Amiga 1200 is 
  authentic (because it is the real deal). An FPGA system that reproduces 
  the Amiga 1200 chips is less authentic and a computer running an 
  emulator is the least authentic. Case closed and we can all go home.

  But can we really? 

  Let's take a closer look at our Amiga 1200.
 
  My Amiga today is fairly modest compared to many systems enthusiasts 
  have built: A 1200 with a fast 68030 card and a few other upgrades. 
  Pretty good but a far cry from the maxed out machines people like to 
  set up. How authentic is that system? Well, the case and board is 
  1992 vintage so that's very authentic. The ROMs are 3.1 so they are 
  authentic enough.
 
  But the accelerator card was made in 2010 and is faster than any 68030 
  available at the time. The hard drive is a compact flash card in an IDE
  adapter, the mouse is a PS2 mouse with an adapter, the joystick is 
  brand new, I've attached a PS2 keyboard using a Lyra and the disk drive
  is a Gotek.

  Do any of those change that this is an authentic system? Well, it must 
  right? All of this is equipment that was not available at the time. But
  at the same time, none of it really adds capabilities that were 
  impossible. The Gotek is much more convenient than a real floppy drive, 
  but it still acts like a floppy drive. My brand new joystick is much 
  more precise than the Quickshots I got off ebay but it's still just a 
  joystick with 9 pin connector and so forth.

  If we had to rate it on a scale from 100 (completely authentic) to 0 
  (completely inauthentic) maybe its around 70?

  It certainly feels authentic when I sit and use it but what was my 
  system like at the time? It was an Amiga 1200 with an external floppy 
  drive and that was it.
 
  For comparison I looked up a Mac from 1992 and my accelerator card has 
  6 times as much RAM and a much faster CPU. My relatively humble Amiga 
  today would have been a beast of a computer in 1992. So clearly my 
  Amiga now cannot be authentic to the experience I had as a 12 year old.

  That is leaving aside the software. Now I can click on a game and 
  through the magic of WHDLoad it loads the game into memory and runs the
  same way it would on a cartridge based system. Meanwhile in 1992 I 
  would have been swapping disks and waiting for the grinding of the disk
  drive (while hoping the rumors that copy protection could destroy your 
  drive were false. I never did find out).

  Would sitting in the dark room with a stack of floppies and an old ball
  mouse be more authentic? Yes. Undeniably so. That IS the authentic 
  Amiga experience for me.

  But would I want to again? Well, I did but I also upgraded my system 
  when I was able to in order to get more functionality or more 
  convenience or more capabilities. 

  So I guess my conclusion is that I am happy with 70% authenticity. And 
  I expect I'll be happy at 80% or at 60%. What is your level of 
  authenticity? What did you build your system to do?

  Take a moment to think about it the next time you boot it up.
@endnode 

@node retrocomputermeetup "Retro Computer Meetup Tokyo?"
@toc articles
============================================================================
		 @{b}Retro Computer Meetup Tokyo@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

  In an attempt to broaden the scope of the magazine we will be starting
  section focusing on local Amiga or retro computer groups/meetups around
  the world.  To start this off we will be looking at the Tokyo Retro 
  Computer Users meet up in Kayabacho, Tokyo.  I had been introduced 
  about this meet up by Edoardo or has he is also known as `kinmami` on 
  EAB.  Last year he had replaced the CAPS and DAC chip on my A1200, 
  making it sing like new again.  A few times he had invited me to attend
  but due to the covid situation I had been hesitant, however now with my
  third vaccine well and done, it was time to venture up to Tokyo.

  I live in Chiba which is about 50 minutes by train to Tokyo station,
  getting to Kayabacho was a short trip of only 47 minutes by rapid train
  on the Keiyo line.  On the train I had my A1200 with me again, ready to
  have the TF1260 firmware updated by Edoardo.  It was quite exciting as
  I had not been out since the covid situation and more so I had not met
  any Amiga users in Japan since I had moved here so I was very much 
  looking forward to meeting similar minded Amiga junkies.

  Upon arriving at Hatchobori station, it was a short walk to the exit
  that would take me to the Co-Edo Co-working Space Kayabacho, according
  to Google maps it should only take 7 minutes.  The map looked very 
  simple but I seem to have any amazing ability to confuse map directions.
  Following the map printout (Yes, I do not have a smartphone and still
  find my way around like it's 2000 again) I ended up on the wrong side 
  of the river, brilliant!  Quickly I backtracked to Hatchobori station 
  and started again, however this time I asked some friendly Tokyoites if
  I was on the right track.  Everyone I asked gave me great directions 
  until I was very close and .... still could not find the place, I
  went to a Lawson convenience store and asked the staff where I could 
  find the Co-Edo building.  He looked at me for long moment, then 
  pointed behind me.  To my surprise there it was behind me, feeling like
  an idiot I apologised and thanked him.

  Finally arriving at the building, it was like most typical Tokyo 
  buildings, thin and tall, the entrance was cramped but effective.  
  The reception was on the 5th floor, when I got there I told them I was
  with Sean, paid my ¥1,100, filled in my details and received my one day
  visitor pass.  From there it was down to the 4th floor to meet the 
  guys for the first time.  Entering the 4th floor, it was refreshingly
  cool thanks to the air-conditioning.  Splitting the room was a
  smoked glass window with the meeting taking place on the other side.
  I cautiously opened the door and the first person I met was Edoardo, 
  I introduced myself and then proceeded to meet the rest of the 
  people there.  This was around 10:30 am and at that time there 
  were not too many people, so it was easy to meet everyone.  Sean is the
  organiser and you can find him walking around taking photos and videos
  asking questions about the various computers that people brought in.

  The room had two main tables and one of them were some very large 
  computers, one being a Casio FP-1100 brought in by Sean.  He kindly
  showed be around the machine and sat me down for game or two.  It
  was a very striking machine that would not look out of place in 
  any of the current electronic stores.  The design was very modern
  looking, aside from the fact that the keyboard cannot be disconnected.
  That it itself would be an issue but the keyboard was almost as big as
  the computer!
  Curt brought in a Basic Master Level 3 computer which was another 
  monster of a computer, unfortunately I never got round to having a play
  on that one.

  The guys there were very friendly and quick to answer any questions
  I had.  If you wanted to try a machine they would you sit down and 
  expliain the machine.

  The atmosphere was very relaxed and friendly, I immediately felt at
  at home there.  After getting introduced to the rest of the guys
  it came time for my TF1260 firmware update, it took a little while 
  longer than expected since Windows had to update, or as Edoardo said
  "It's plug and pray!", luckily the update went without hitch and then
  it was on to my TF1260.  The firmware was fast, pretty much instant.
  From there on the Amiga would just sit doing some tasks to check its 
  stability.

  A little later some more people arrived, first Michelle with a massive
  suitcase, upon opening it up she had a NEC PC-8801MA plus 14" CRT 
  monitor, it must have been quite a journey for her lugging all 35kg of
  that from Yokohama.

  However as being someone who does not have the money or space to
  buy other computers this was a fantastic opportunity to get up close 
  with rare computers and even try the out.  Michelle introduced me to 
  one of the most difficult games I have ever played, Warpman, I think I 
  demonstrated my lack of gaming skills quite well during that time.
  Michelle tried her best to guide me how to play the game but my hands
  and brain seemed to be doing the opposite of what I wanted.

  Shortly after Michelle arrived Robert another newcomer came in lugging
  another huge box, this was going to the highlight of the day for many
  people as when he unwrapped the computer it was a SGI Iris Indigo.  
  Suffice to say many of us had our interest peaked at the sight of that
  rare beast.  The next few hours flew by as we played with the various 
  hardware talked shop, computers and games.  It turned out that Robert 
  was another EAB member and was an Amiga user, bringing the total of 
  Amiga guys to three at the meet up.  Suffice to say talk quickly moved
  to the Amiga, it seems no matter in the world if you have Amiga users 
  they are happy as ducks in water to fritter the hours away talking 
  about the Amiga.

  Sven was originally working on his Z80 mini PC, a very cute looking
  computer, but when Robert unveilved his SGI all thoughts of the Z80 were 
  gone.  As the day passed on more and more people turned up, unfortunately 
  I did not have the chance to talk to all them.  Saburo I am sorry I did 
  not have a chance to chat to, hopefully we can talk properly next time.  

  Overall it was a great day, meeting people interested in old computers
  and the chance to see and touch some incredibly rare computers was 
  great fun.  The fact that the owners there are happy to tell you about
  the computer's history, how to use them and answer any questions you may 
  have, makes it a very welcoming and enjoyable event.  If you are an 
  Amiga user or retro computer collector and want to spend time with 
  similar minded people then I recommend attending an event.  I will be
  attending the next event at the end of August or early September with my
  A1200 for another firmware update to be done and maybe have an FPU socket
  installed onto the motherboard.

  If you live Tokyo or Chiba and are an Amiga user I hope we can see you at
  the next event!
@endnode 

@node talkingamiga "Welcome to voices of the people behind Amiga hardware and software."
@toc contents
============================================================================
                  	  @{b}-  Talking Amiga -@{ub}
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

   @{"                  -=  Edoardo Auteri Interview  =-                   " link edoardo}  
   Continuing our focus on Japan this issue, we talk to Edoardo, a
   Tokyo resident servicing the needs of Amiga users around Japan.
   @{"                   -=  Pawel Nowak Interview  =-                     " link pawel}
   The author of Infinity Music Player or IMP, we talk about Pawel's 
   history with computers and the Amiga.  Find out more inside!

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
           #Talking Amiga - WhatIFF? Issue 1.06 - August 2022#   
@endnode

@node edoardo "Edoardo Auteri"
@toc talkingamiga
 
  @{b}Edoardo, thank you for taking the time to answer our questions.@{ub}

  @{b}Can you tell us a little about yourself?@{ub}

  Hello, glad to be here. Thank you for the fantastic opportunity.
  My name is Edoardo Auteri, European, born in Italy in 1977. I moved to
  Asia in 2010 and from 2014 working and living in Tokyo. I am fascinated
  by the eighties of which I keep vivid memories and try to replicate the
  best aspects in everyday life. I am working in the semiconductor 
  industry since 1997.

  @{b}How did you get started with computers?@{ub}

  I have always been interested in electronic games and entertainment. 
  When possible, I would go to arcades to play games in the eighties. In
  1985 a school mate invited me home for Sunday lunch and afternoon 
  study. His father challenged us to play Zaxxon with the Commodore 128 
  he just bought. I was impressed with the isometric view, collisions, 
  and sound effects. Also playing with a paddle was a memorable 
  experience as I just used the arcade joysticks. My first home computer
  was the Commodore 64C given to me by my parents in Christmas 1986. And
  from that moment on I have not stopped interested in hardware.

  @{b}What was your first Amiga experience?@{ub}

  My first model was the Amiga 500 purchased in the summer of 1988. 
  Advertisements in newspapers and television channels were rife in 
  Italy. There was a murmur in classrooms about "a new home computer 
  capable of speaking voices and playing orchestral music". I was using 
  the C64 with satisfaction, yet I was curious. I first tried the A500 at
  friends' and Commodore dealers in late 1987. Japanese consoles, Atari, 
  and Spectrum did not shock me (not yet at least) while I was thrilled 
  by the idea that a new Commodore model could go beyond the potential of 
  the C64.

  @{b}What attracted you to working with Amiga hardware?@{ub}

  The genius in the design of the custom chips and the flexibility of 
  the Amiga structure represent an immense interest in improving, 
  expanding performance. Furthermore, the possibility of managing audio 
  and video with relative ease achieving results comparable (for the 80s
  and 90s) to television studios was astounding. Both on C64 and on Amiga
  I experimented with DIY boards connected to serial, parallel and 
  expansion ports. I wrote high- and low-level language programs. In 
  short, I prepared myself for the future study and work. I would not be 
  in Tokyo, and I would not deal with technology and semiconductors if 
  I had not kept practicing in depth with Commodore Amiga.

  @{b}What kind of work do you do on the Amiga?@{ub}

  Nowadays I delight in repairing all models. From a simple replacement 
  of worn capacitors and logics to the modification/fixing of old 
  original layout boards. Continuing with the design and prototyping of
  new expansion cards, adapters, and accessories that I usually share 
  with the community (EAB, Discord, Hackaday and PCBWay). Sometimes I 
  like to load and run classic games of course.

  @{b}You currently live in Japan, what brought you to Japan?@{ub}

  Japan strongly influenced my Italian childhood. I do not remember 
  anything other than fashions, hobbies, entertainment directly or 
  indirectly imported from Japan. I am not a fanatic of everything made 
  in Japan. However, I appreciate good manners, respect for one's word, 
  lifestyle. These are aspects that Italy has only partially been able 
  to perpetuate. Before Tokyo I lived and worked in Seoul, Shenzhen, 
  Singapore in the semiconductor market.

  @{b}Can you describe the current Amiga scene in Japan?@{ub}

  I know few Commodore Amiga enthusiasts and collectors in Japan. These 
  are not usually gents and ladies experimenting with their machines. 
  Friendly people interested in news. They were even former employees of 
  the Japanese branch of Commodore (they showed photos with Jay Miner). 
  There are also friends from the US, UK and Australia living in Japan 
  and using Amigas. They are running YouTube channels in English and 
  Japanese showing the pixel art, and hardware & software tutorials, for
  example.

  @{b}You are one-half of the Ramixx500 Amiga 500+ Main board replacement 
  project, can you tell us a little behind the idea?@{ub}

  The project author is Giorgio Moscardi, known as Sukkopera. He is based
  in Turin, Italy. All credits to Giorgio and his formidable ability 
  and meticulousness. I validated the project by bench evaluation, 
  finding bugs, and suggesting Giorgio improvements. The purpose of the 
  project, well explained on Hackaday, is to improve the original concept
  to preserve the design and make it usable at reasonable prices. Sordan
  (Ireland) is the online shop that helps supporting the project. Thanks
  to Giorgio for his extraordinary effort.

  @{b}What kind of improvements do you plan to incorporate into the new 
  motherboard?@{ub}

  We have redesigned the power and ground planes. Additionally, we have 
  done a more reasonable selection of the Bill Of Materials list, added
  video sync buffer, jumpers to switch among internal/external FDD, HDD 
  led activity circuit, ESD protections, etc. We have worked out a new 
  Video Hybrid, also known as VIDIOT, able to output 15KHz colorful 
  composite and S-VIDEO signals for the A500 and A2000, A3000.

  @{b}You are working on a new motherboard however the board will need 
  original chips, do you think it will be possible to re-create all the 
  custom chips allowing the Amigas to live on for longer in physical form?@{ub}

  In theory anything can be reprogrammed using a proper FPGA. In fact, 
  there are tentative of making a brand-new FATTER AGNUS, DENISE, etc. 
  For example, BUSTER for A2000 is implemented with a FPGA and available 
  to users. The 680xx microprocessor itself is entirely reinvented with 
  FPGA and will be available soon. Dave Haynie is studying an improved 
  version of SUPER BUSTER for the A3000 and A4000. Today the market does 
  suffer the shortage then projects slowed down or stopped. We will see 
  how things will go after 2025, I suppose.

  @{b}What Amigas do you own? If you have any other types of computers please
  feel free to mention them.@{ub}

  Various models of A500/+, A600, A1000 (and Phoenix), A2000, A1200, 
  A3000, A4000 (desktop), CD32, CDTV. In addition to C16, Plus4, C64,
  C128, Sony/Toshiba/Casio MSX, MSX2+, Sharp X68000XVI, Atari 800XL, 
  Atari 1040 STE and vintage consoles from Nintendo, Panasonic, and 
  Sega. I miss Amiga tower versions, but I own all motherboard/hardware
  desktop revisions, including SAM460ex.

  @{b}What is your main Amiga setup?@{ub}

  A1200 with TF1260 accelerator, kickstart 3.2, Flash Floppy drive and 
  CF HDD. Definitely 32bit AGA based.

  @{b}What would your dream Amiga be?@{ub}

  It is nice to see that over the past twelve months they have released 
  (numerically) more quality games and enhanced versions of classics of 
  Amiga than new Sony PS5 releases. There is excitement and there are 
  innate talents working from behind the scenes. I would like to play 
  the Street Fighter II Champion Edition conversion built out of 
  Scorpion Engine actually. I have no dreams of new hardware/accessories.

  Stakeholders need new software applications and tools. I hope that the
  global Commodore / Amiga community will become more supportive, 
  meritocratic, open-minded, and put aside feelings of hatred and 
  greediness.

