@node pawel "Pawel Nowak Interview"
@toc talkingamiga

  @{b}Pawel Nowak, thank you for taking the time to answer our questions.@{ub}
 
  @{b}Can you tell us a little about yourself?@{ub}

  I'm Pawel, I live in Poland, specifically in Krakow. Professionally 
  deals with programming. I also have my own small printing company which
  I also use in the retro world - I publish games in large boxes, CDs or 
  even cassettes. I'm 39 so I'm still very young :-) I have a wonderful 
  wife and two children. I don't have as much time for my hobby as I used
  to, but I try to support the Amiga market as much as I can. I am also a
  collector of old computer junk.

  @{b}How did you get started with computers?@{ub}

  My first computer (when I was 7) was the Atari XE. It is thanks to him 
  that I learned what it means to program. After about two years, I was 
  able to exchange it for the Amige 500, which was a total novelty for 
  me. I had no idea there was such a thing as a computer mouse. What the
  Amiga offered exceeded all expectations. I stuck to my A500 for a long
  time, everyone around them had a great A1200 with 030 and 040, and I 
  was still faithful to my A500. Finally my friends convinced me and I 
  bought a used A1200. I could do anything on it. After a while I got 
  Blizzard PPC. This adventure continued for a few more years until my 
  card broke. for about 10 years I lost my interest in Amiga. After this 
  time, I started collecting retro gear, including going back to the 
  amiga and starting coding again.

  
  @{b}What was your first Amiga experience?@{ub}

  After replacing Atari with Amige in 1992, I was still a kid, but I 
  already had some knowledge of how to use a computer efficiently and 
  could deepen it further. I was interested in games on the average, 
  one day we bought VBS, and this opened access to huge collections of 
  software, disk magazines and other productions from the demoscene. 
  At that time, in Poland, no one was concerned about copyright. On 
  the one hand, it is bad because it was hard for people to give up 
  piracy later, and on the other hand, it made development possible. 
  I started to get to know new contacts, with whom I exchanged letters, 
  until I got to the right people and entered the scene as a swapper, 
  I started going to an Amiga party and got into it all totally. In 
  the last days of my swapper life I belonged to groups such as 
  Appendix, Nah-Kolor or Mawi.

  @{b}What attracted you to working with Amiga hardware?@{ub}

  The Motorola 68k is the most attractive software processor I know. You
  don't need a lot of knowledge to quickly learn its secrets and start 
  writing your own code. Amiga hardware is a great fun environment for 
  both beginners and advanced players. You can do everything your way 
  and enjoy the final result even if the requirements are greater than 
  the goal of the A500 Amiga. Amiga and assembler is the best 
  combination.

  @{b}What kind of work do you do on the Amiga?@{ub}

  It's quite simple in my case - 90% of the time I sit on IMP (a lot is 
  happening on our Polish channel), 10% watch demos. Sometimes I bend 
  these proportions and check new programs or games.

  @{b}You live in Poland, can you describe the Amiga scene there?@{ub}

  The Amiga scene in Poland has always been large, both in the times of 
  the amiga's glory, when a lot of demoscene productions were created, 
  as well as now, when the demoscene is no longer active, but various 
  types of meetings, just amiga owners, the larger and smaller ones take 
  place all the time in various corners of our country. I have friends a 
  few hundred km away, and it seems to me that I meet them every now and 
  then, and meeting someone after many years is my everyday life. A lot 
  of people come back to using amiga, despite the fact that in our 
  country, probably everyone is as busy as possible :)

  @{b}Infinity Music Player (IMP) was your creation, what other Amiga 
  software did make before IMP?@{ub}

  On aminet.net you can find some of my programs, some have been there for
  over 20 years. From newer stuff, someone may associate me with games 
  that I create in the Project R3D group, such as Tanks Furry, Bridge 
  Strike, Zgr3d or Astro Blox Revisited - all are available for free 
  download on aminet.net or in a physical version (box) on the website 
  www.cdlabel.eu

  @{b}What gave the idea to create IMP?@{ub}

  I was looking for an idea for a network program. In general, I was 
  interested in how to program the internet in amiga. First, I thought 
  about a game that would use it, for example for online play. But such
  a game would take years to develop, so I was still looking for new 
  ideas, and finally it dawned on me that having a show collection of 
  modules, it could be easily used and then the first version of the 
  IMP was created, which worked exclusively in CLI, loaded a random 
  module one by one (it additionally buffered them, to play next one 
  right away). The idea was well received in the community and I 
  immediately started adding more stuff, information about samples, 
  preview of patterns played (still in CLI :)), number of online users, 
  simple chat etc, until it turned out that the GUI version was inevitable.

  @{b}There must have been many hurdles during the project, what were some 
  of the most difficult ones?@{ub}

  The hardest part was bsdsocket.library, which was news to me, and there 
  is not much documentation for the assembler. Something that worked on 
  the winuae wasn't working on a real amiga, then something that worked 
  on miami didn't work elsewhere, something that already worked on every 
  tcp / ip stack suddenly had problems with different drivers - 
  especially atypical NICs for large amigos. Modules player clashed with 
  interrupts, etc. In the end, all the problems were solved - thanks to 
  the people who tested the program (because I do not have access to 
  every possible configuration myself at home)

  @{b}The software has many features already, do you plan to improve or add 
  to the program?@{ub}

  At this stage, there is no greater need for software development, but 
  sometimes you suddenly get an idea and implement it. I don't think too 
  much about it anymore. However, I am developing an additional thing 
  that will soon see the light of day. It is an impbox - an esp32 based 
  device plugged into a parallel port in the amiga. Thanks to it, the 
  imp does not need an Internet connection, the wifi module in the impbox
  is used to communicate with the server, so the strobe configuration on 
  the Amiga side is omitted, more memory remains in the amiga itself. 
  Impbox is equipped with a display with information about logged in 
  users, vumeter. It is still a development issue, but it works quite 
  steadily. the basic cdtv amiga achieved a transfer of around 70kb/s, 
  which beats the plipbox you know at the moment.

  @{b}What Amigas do you own?@{ub}

  Currently I have 36 amiga, and a lot of other computers and consoles. 
  There would be no space to describe it, but when someone visits me, 
  you can always count on a little tour and getting to know my 
  collection. An almost up-to-date list can be found here 
  http://szajb.us

  @{b}What is your main Amiga setup?@{ub}

  I have used many amiga interchangeably. The most common are amiga with
  warp1260, amiga 4000 with 060 and zz9k (with additional sound card), 
  amiga 2000 with tf536 and amiga 500 with aca1233n. I also turn on my 
  cdtv from 010 a lot to test the impa as well. In the second apartment 
  I have a600 with v2 which I use only for imp and testing the impbox.

  @{b}What would your dream Amiga be?@{ub}
 
  I haven't looked at it in such terms for a long time. Amiga with aga 
  and fast 060 is all that is enough for me to demoscene. Older 
  productions can be run on any other. I miss a4k mediator a bit to take
  advantage of the PPC (bigfoot) that lies and waits in the desk drawer,
  and to have access to the rest of the ppc demos. Here, the equipment 
  with morphos comes to the rescue, which fill me up a bit. I can enjoy 
  any amiga with no matter what configuration and I don't need anything 
  else.

  @{b}Thank you for your time Pawel, do you have any final words or anything
  you would like to mention?@{ub}

  Thank you that you are still with the amiga, for me it is a huge chunk 
  of my life and something that shaped me in its own way, I cannot 
  imagine my life without it now. Thank you all for your great support, 
  turning a blind eye to various inconveniences in my productions, for 
  healthy criticism and for the fact that we have something to talk 
  about. 

  Thank you for inviting me to this interview, it's great that such 
  magazines are still coming out in the Amiga media world.

@endnode

